# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: botanic-gardens-conservation-international
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens-conservation-international] Founded in 1987, BGCI is a registered charity in the United Kingdom, and its members include the Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew and the Royal Botanic Garden, Edinburgh, as two of its key supporters.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens-conservation-international] The founder and director from 1987 to 1993 was Professor Vernon H Heywood.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens-conservation-international] Peter Wyse Jackson (as Secretary-General) who led BGCI till 2005 when Sara Oldfield succeeded him.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens-conservation-international] She was then followed by Paul Smith in 2016 (current acting Secretary-General of BGCI).
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens-conservation-international] Lady Suzanne Warner was Chair of BGCI from December 1999 to December 2004.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens-conservation-international] She received an OBE in the Queen's 2006 New Year's Honours for her services to plant conservation.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens-conservation-international] Dedicated to plant conservation and environmental education, the charity works to support and promote the activities of its member gardens.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens-conservation-international] As a global organisation BGCI has projects in a variety of different countries, with major ongoing projects in China (where half of the wild magnolias are threatened), North America, the Middle East and Russia.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens-conservation-international] Two of its major projects are the creation of on-line searchable databases listing the world's botanic gardens (Garden Search) and plants in cultivation among participating botanic gardens (Plant Search).
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens-conservation-international] The group also found that 5 billion people benefit from traditional plant-based medicine for health care.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens-conservation-international] In 2017 Botanic Gardens Conservation International published a list of 60,065 tree species worldwide obtained from information supplied by its member organisations.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens-conservation-international] The aim of the project was to identify trees that are in danger of extinction and promote efforts to conserve these trees.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens-conservation-international] In 2021 BGCI published a landmark State of the World's Trees report.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens-conservation-international] The report, compiling work led by the Global Tree Assessment (GTA), is the culmination of five years of research to identify major gaps in tree conservation efforts.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens-conservation-international] It is one of the first assessments of the world's threatened trees.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens-conservation-international] Examining the globe's 60,000 tree species, it reveals that 30% (17,500) of tree species are currently at risk of extinction.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens-conservation-international] That means there are twice the number of threatened tree species globally than threatened mammals, birds, amphibians and reptiles combined.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens-conservation-international] The State of the World's Trees report brings together research from over 60 institutional partners, including botanic gardens, forestry institutions and universities worldwide, as well as more than 500 experts who have contributed to tree assessments in the last five years.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] A **botanical garden** or **botanic garden** is a garden with a documented collection of living plants for the purpose of scientific research, conservation, display, and education.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Plants in larger gardens are often labelled with their botanical names and additional information.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] It may contain specialist plant collections such as cacti and other succulent plants, herb gardens, or plants from particular parts of the world.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] There may be glasshouses or shadehouses with special collections such as tropical plants, alpine plants, or other exotic plants that are not native to the local region.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Most are at least partly open to the public, and may offer guided tours, public programming such as workshops, courses, educational displays, art exhibitions, book rooms, open-air theatrical and musical performances, and other entertainment.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Botanical gardens are often run by universities or other scientific research organizations, and usually have associated herbaria and research programmes in plant taxonomy or some other aspect of botanical science.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] In principle, their role is to maintain documented collections of living plants for the purposes of scientific research, conservation, display, and education, although this will depend on the resources available and the special interests pursued at each particular garden.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] The staff will normally include botanists as well as gardeners.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Many botanical gardens offer diploma or certificate programs in horticulture, botany and taxonomy.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] There are many internship opportunities offered to aspiring horticulturists, as well as opportunities for students and researchers to use the collection for their studies.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] The *New Royal Horticultural Society Dictionary of Gardening* (1999) points out that among the various kinds of organizations known as botanical gardens, there are many that are in modern times public gardens with little scientific activity.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] The following definition was produced by staff of the Liberty Hyde Bailey Hortorium of Cornell University in 1976.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] All botanical gardens have their own special interests.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] In a paper on the role of botanical gardens, Ferdinand von Mueller (1825–1896), the director of the Royal Botanic Gardens, Melbourne (1852–1873), stated, "in all cases the objects [of a botanical garden] must be mainly scientific and predominantly instructive".
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] He detailed many of the objectives being pursued by the world's botanical gardens in the middle of the 19th century, when European gardens were at their height.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Historically, botanical gardens have responded to the interests and values of the day.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] If a single function were to be chosen from the early literature on botanical gardens, it would be their scientific endeavour and, flowing from this, their instructional value.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] In their formative years, botanical gardens were gardens for physicians and botanists, but they became more associated with ornamental horticulture and the needs of the general public.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] The scientific reputation of a botanical garden is judged by the publications coming out of herbaria and similar facilities, not by its living collections.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Their focus has been on creating an awareness of the threat to the Earth's ecosystems from human populations and the consequent need for biological and physical resources.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Botanical gardens provide an excellent medium for communication between the world of botanical science and the general public.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Education programs can help the public develop greater environmental awareness by understanding the meaning and importance of ideas like conservation and sustainability.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Worldwide, there are now about 1800 botanical gardens and arboreta in about 150 countries (mostly in temperate regions) of which about 550 are in Europe (150 of which are in Russia), 200 in North America, and an increasing number in East Asia.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] These gardens attract about 300 million visitors a year.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Historically, botanical gardens exchanged plants through the publication of seed lists (called Latin: *Indices Seminum* in the 18th century).
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] This was a means of transferring both plants and information between botanical gardens.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] This system continues today, though with attention to the risks of genetic piracy and transmission of invasive species.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] The International Association of Botanic Gardens was formed in 1954 as a worldwide organisation affiliated to the International Union of Biological Sciences.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] More recently, coordination has also been provided by Botanic Gardens Conservation International (BGCI), which has the mission "To mobilise botanic gardens and engage partners in securing plant diversity for the well-being of people and the planet".
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Regional coordination is seen in the United States with the American Public Gardens Association (formerly the American Association of Botanic Gardens and Arboreta), while in Australasia there is the Botanic Gardens of Australia and New Zealand (BGANZ).
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] The history of botanical gardens is closely linked to the history of botany itself.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] The botanical gardens of the 16th and 17th centuries were medicinal gardens, but the idea of a botanical garden changed to encompass displays of the beautiful, strange, new, and sometimes economically important plant trophies being returned from the European colonies and other distant lands.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] In the 18th century, they became more educational in function, demonstrating the latest plant classification systems devised by botanists working in the associated herbaria as they tried to order these new treasures.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Then, in the 19th and 20th centuries, the trend was towards a combination of specialist and eclectic collections demonstrating aspects of both horticulture and botany.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] The idea of "scientific" gardens used specifically for the study of plants dates back to antiquity.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] The origin of modern botanical gardens is generally traced to the appointment of botany professors to the medical faculties of universities in 16th-century Renaissance Italy, which entailed curating a medicinal garden.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] However, the objectives, content, and audience of today's botanic gardens more closely resemble that of the grandiose gardens of antiquity and the educational garden of Theophrastus in the Lyceum of ancient Athens.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Near-Eastern royal gardens, set aside for economic use or display and containing at least some plants gained by special collecting trips or military campaigns abroad, are known from the second millennium BCE in ancient Egypt, Mesopotamia, Crete, Mexico and China.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] In about 2800 BCE, the Chinese Emperor Shen Nung sent collectors to distant regions searching for plants with economic or medicinal value.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] It has also been suggested that the Spanish colonization of Mesoamerica influenced the history of the botanical garden.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Early medieval gardens in Islamic Spain resembled later botanic gardens, an example being the 11th-century Huerta del Rey garden of physician and author Ibn Wafid (999–1075 CE) in Toledo.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] This was taken over by garden chronicler Ibn Bassal (fl.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] 1085 CE) until the Christian conquest in 1085 CE.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Ibn Bassal then founded a garden in Seville, most of its plants being collected on a botanical expedition that included Morocco, Persia, Sicily, and Egypt.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] The medical school of Montpellier was also founded by Spanish Arab physicians, and by 1250 CE, it included a physic garden, but the site was not given botanic garden status until 1593.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Botanical gardens developed from physic gardens, whose main purpose was to cultivate herbs for medical use as well as research and experimentation.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] In Europe, for example, Aristotle (384 BCE – 322 BCE) is said to have had a physic garden in the Lyceum at Athens, which was used for educational purposes and for the study of botany.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] This was inherited, or possibly set up, by his pupil Theophrastus, the "Father of Botany".
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] There is some debate among science historians whether this garden was ordered and scientific enough to be considered "botanical"; instead, they attribute the earliest known botanical garden in Europe to the botanist and pharmacologist Antonius Castor, mentioned by Pliny the Elder in the 1st century.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] The forerunners of modern botanical gardens are generally regarded as being the medieval monastic physic gardens that originated after the decline of the Roman Empire at the time of Emperor Charlemagne (742–789 CE).
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] These contained a *hortus*, a garden used mostly for vegetables, and another section set aside for specially labelled medicinal plants; this was called the *herbularis* or *hortus medicus*—more generally known as a physic garden—and a *viridarium* or orchard.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Such gardens were given impetus by Charlemagne's Capitulary de Villis, which listed 73 herbs to be used in the physic gardens of his dominions.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Many of these had already been introduced to British gardens.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Pope Nicholas V set aside part of the Vatican grounds in 1447 for a garden of medicinal plants that were used to promote the teaching of botany, and this was a forerunner to the University gardens at Padua and Pisa established in the 1540s.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Certainly, the founding of many early botanic gardens was instigated by members of the medical profession.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] In the 17th century, botanical gardens began their contribution to a deeper scientific curiosity about plants.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] If a botanical garden is defined by its scientific or academic connection, then the first true botanical gardens were established with the revival of learning that occurred in the European Renaissance.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] These were secular gardens attached to universities and medical schools, used as resources for teaching and research.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] The superintendents of these gardens were often professors of botany with international reputations, a factor that probably contributed to the creation of botany as an independent discipline rather than a descriptive adjunct to medicine.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Here the physicians (known in English as apothecaries) delivered lectures on the Mediterranean "simples" or "officinals" that were being cultivated in the grounds.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Student education was no doubt stimulated by the relatively recent advent of printing and the publication of the first herbals.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] During the 16th and 17th centuries, the first plants were being imported to these major Western European gardens from Eastern Europe and nearby Asia (which provided many bulbs), and these found a place in the new gardens, where they could be conveniently studied by the plant experts of the day.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] For example, Asian introductions were described by Carolus Clusius (1526–1609), who was director, in turn, of the Botanical Garden of the University of Vienna and Hortus Botanicus Leiden.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Many plants were being collected from the Near East, especially bulbous plants from Turkey.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Clusius laid the foundations of Dutch tulip breeding and the bulb industry, and he helped create one of the earliest formal botanical gardens of Europe at Leyden where his detailed planting lists have made it possible to recreate this garden near its original site.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] The *hortus medicus* of Leyden in 1601 was a perfect square divided into quarters for the four continents, but by 1720, though, it was a rambling system of beds, struggling to contain the novelties rushing in, and it became better known as the *hortus academicus*.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] His *Exoticorum libri decem* (1605) is an important survey of exotic plants and animals that is still consulted today.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] In the mid to late 17th century, the Paris Jardin des Plantes was a centre of interest with the greatest number of new introductions to attract the public.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] In England, the Chelsea Physic Garden was founded in 1673 as the "Garden of the Society of Apothecaries".
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] The Chelsea garden had heated greenhouses, and in 1723 appointed Philip Miller (1691–1771) as head gardener.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] He had a wide influence on both botany and horticulture, as plants poured into it from around the world.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] The garden's golden age came in the 18th century, when it became the world's most richly stocked botanical garden.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Its seed-exchange programme was established in 1682 and still continues today.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] With the increase in maritime trade, ever more plants were brought back to Europe as trophies from distant lands, and these were triumphantly displayed in the private estates of the wealthy, in commercial nurseries, and in the public botanical gardens.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Heated conservatories called "orangeries" became a feature of many botanical gardens.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] The Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew, was founded in 1759, initially as part of the Royal Garden set aside as a physic garden.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] William Aiton (1741–1793), the first curator, was taught by garden chronicler Philip Miller of the Chelsea Physic Garden, whose son Charles became the first curator of the original Cambridge Botanic Garden (1762).
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] In 1759, the "Physick Garden" was planted, and by 1767, it was claimed that "the Exotick Garden is by far the richest in Europe".
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] From the 1770s, following the example of the French and Spanish, amateur collectors were supplemented by official horticultural and botanical plant hunters.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] These botanical gardens were boosted by the flora being sent back to Europe from various European colonies around the globe.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] At the end of the 18th century, Kew, under the directorship of Sir Joseph Banks, enjoyed a golden age of plant hunting, sending out collectors to the South African Cape, Australia, Chile, China, Ceylon, Brazil, and elsewhere, and acting as "the great botanical exchange house of the British Empire".
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] From its earliest days to the present, Kew has in many ways exemplified botanic garden ideals, and is respected worldwide for the published work of its scientists, the education of horticultural students, its public programmes, and the scientific underpinning of its horticulture.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] In 1728, John Bartram founded Bartram's Garden in Philadelphia, one of the continent's first botanical gardens.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] The garden is now managed as a historical site that includes a few original and many modern specimens as well as extensive archives and restored historical farm buildings.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] The large number of plants needing description were listed in garden catalogues; and from 1753 Carl Linnaeus established the system of binomial nomenclature which greatly facilitated the listing process.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Names of plants were authenticated by dried plant specimens mounted on card (a *hortus siccus* or garden of dried plants) that were stored in buildings called herbaria.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] These taxonomic research institutions were frequently associated with the botanical gardens, many of which by then had "order beds" to display the classification systems being developed by botanists in the gardens' museums and herbaria.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Botanical gardens became scientific collections, as botanists published their descriptions of the new exotic plants, and these were recorded for posterity in detail by superb botanical illustrations.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] The late 18th and early 19th centuries were marked by the establishment of tropical botanical gardens as a tool of colonial expansion (for trade and commerce and, secondarily, science) mainly by the British and Dutch, in India, South-east Asia, and the Caribbean.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] This was also the time of Sir Joseph Banks's botanical collections during Captain James Cook's circumnavigations of the planet and his explorations of Oceania, with plant introductions on a grand scale.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] There are currently about 230 tropical botanical gardens, many of them in southern and south-eastern Asia.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] The first botanical garden founded in the tropics was the Pamplemousses Botanical Garden in Mauritius, established in 1735 to provide food for ships using the port, but later trialling and distributing many plants of economic importance.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] This was followed by the West Indies (Saint Vincent and the Grenadines Botanic Gardens, 1764) and in 1786 by the Acharya Jagadish Chandra Bose Botanical Garden in Calcutta, India, founded during a period of prosperity when the city was a trading centre for the Dutch East India Company.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Other gardens were constructed in Brazil (Rio de Janeiro Botanical Garden, 1808), Sri Lanka (Botanic Gardens of Peradeniya, 1821, on a site dating back to 1371), Indonesia (Bogor Botanical Gardens, 1817 and Kebun Raya Cibodas, 1852), and Singapore (Singapore Botanical Gardens, 1822).
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] These had a profound effect on the economy of the countries, especially in relation to the foods and medicines introduced.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] The importation of rubber trees to the Singapore Botanic Garden initiated the important rubber industry of the Malay Peninsula.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] At this time also, teak and tea were introduced to India, and breadfruit, pepper, and starfruit to the Caribbean.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Included in the charter of these gardens was the investigation of the local flora for its economic potential to both the colonists and the local people.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Many crop plants were introduced by or through these gardens—often in association with European botanical gardens such as Kew or Amsterdam—and included cloves, tea, coffee, breadfruit, cinchona, sugar, cotton, palm oil, and *Theobroma cacao* (for chocolate).
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] During these times, the rubber plant was introduced to Singapore.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Especially in the tropics, the larger gardens were frequently associated with a herbarium and museum of economy.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] The Botanical Garden of Peradeniya had considerable influence on the development of agriculture in Ceylon where the Para rubber tree (*Hevea brasiliensis*) was introduced from Kew, which had itself imported the plant from South America.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Other examples include cotton from the Chelsea Physic Garden to the Province of Georgia in 1732 and tea into India by the Calcutta Botanic Garden.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] The transfer of germplasm between the temperate and tropical botanical gardens was undoubtedly responsible for the range of agricultural crops currently used in several regions of the tropics.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] The first botanical gardens in Australia were founded early in the 19th century: the Royal Botanic Gardens, Sydney, 1816; the Royal Tasmanian Botanical Gardens, 1818; the Royal Botanic Gardens, Melbourne, 1845; Adelaide Botanic Gardens, 1854; and Brisbane Botanic Gardens, 1855.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] These were established essentially as colonial gardens of economic botany and acclimatisation.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] South Africa has 10 national botanical gardens, all overseen by the South African National Biodiversity Institute.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] The oldest in South Africa is the 1851 Durban Botanic Gardens.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] The Kirstenbosch National Botanical Garden is the most famous and developed garden in the country, established in 1913 on a site dating to 1848.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] It covers 36 hectares, with an additional 528 hectares of mountainside wilderness forming part of the garden.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Stellenbosch University Botanical Garden is South Africa's oldest university botanical garden; it was established in 1922.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Also in the country is the Karoo Desert National Botanical Garden, founded in 1921 and relocated in 1945.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Elsewhere in Africa, Orman Garden at Giza in Egypt was founded in 1875.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Presidents George Washington, Thomas Jefferson, and James Madison, all experienced farmers, shared the dream of a national botanic garden, leading to the founding in 1820 of the United States Botanic Garden, next to the Capitol in Washington DC.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] In 1859, the Missouri Botanical Garden was founded at St Louis, Missouri; it is one of the world's leading gardens specializing in tropical plants.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Russia's botanical gardens include Moscow University Botanic Garden ('the Apothecary Garden'), founded in 1706 by Tsar Peter the Great, and the Saint Petersburg Botanical Garden, (1714).
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] A large number of civic or municipal botanical gardens were founded in the 19th and 20th centuries.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] These did not develop scientific facilities or programmes, but the horticultural aspects were strong and the plants often labelled.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] They were botanical gardens in the sense of building up collections of plants and exchanging seeds with other gardens around the world, although their collection policies were determined by those in day-to-day charge of them.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] They tended to become little more than beautifully maintained parks and were, indeed, often under general parks administrations.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] The second half of the 20th century saw increasingly sophisticated educational, visitor service, and interpretation services.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Specialised gardens like the Palmengarten in Frankfurt, Germany (1869), one of the world's leading orchid and succulent plant collections, have been very popular.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] With decreasing financial support from governments, revenue-raising public entertainment increased, including music, art exhibitions, special botanical exhibitions, theatre and film, this being supplemented by the advent of "Friends" organisations and the use of volunteer guides.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Plant conservation and the heritage value of exceptional historic landscapes were treated with a growing sense of urgency through the 20th century.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Specialist gardens were sometimes given a separate or adjoining site to display native and indigenous plants.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] In the 1970s, gardens became focused on plant conservation.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] The Botanic Gardens Conservation Secretariat was established by the IUCN and the World Conservation Union in 1987 with the aim of coordinating the plant conservation efforts of botanical gardens around the world.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] It maintains a database of rare and endangered species in botanical gardens' living collections.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Many gardens hold *ex situ* conservation collections that preserve genetic variation.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Collections are often held and cultivated with the intention of reintroduction to their original habitats.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Botanical gardens have continued to be built in the 21st century, such as the first botanical garden in Oman, which is planned to be one of the largest gardens in the world, with the first large-scale cloud forest in a huge glasshouse.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Development of botanical gardens in China over recent years has been remarkable, including the Hainan Botanical Garden of Tropical Economic Plants at Guangzhou, South China Botanical Garden, the Xishuangbanna Botanical Garden of Tropical Plants, and the Xiamen Botanic Garden.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] In developed countries, on the other hand, many have closed for lack of financial support, especially those attached to universities.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] The Palestine Museum of Natural History has a botanic garden, which has been described as a site of nation-building and resistance by Silvia Hassouna.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] The Center for Plant Conservation at St Louis, Missouri, coordinates the conservation of native North American species.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] The 2006 *North American Botanic Garden Strategy for Plant Conservation* sets out its goals to document and conserve plant diversity, to use that diversity sustainably, to educate the public about plant diversity, build conservation capacity, and to build support for the strategy itself.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] A 2024 review in a special issue of the *Journal of Zoological and Botanical Gardens* on the sustainability of botanic gardens noted their increasing roles in conservation and research, and the many new gardens created since 1950.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] In its view, the gardens are being "reinvent[ed]" to serve the goals of conservation, sustainability, and social engagement.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] It observes that historically, the gardens emerged in an era that saw both the growth of modern science and the colonial era.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] In response, the gardens have engaged in decolonising and in "new socio-environmental missions".
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Finally, it attempts to view the gardens on a global scale.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] A 2023 historical review by Chinese botanists similarly notes the long history of botanical gardens from the medicinal gardens of the first universities in Renaissance Europe, and from China's ancient Shennong herbal garden tradition.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] The gardens have in its view continuously adapted to new demands in a changing environment, coming to serve the "core mission of *ex situ* conservation".
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Botanical gardens must find a compromise between the need for peace and seclusion, while at the same time satisfying the public need for information and visitor services that include restaurants, information centres and sales areas that bring with them rubbish, noise, and crowding.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Attractive landscaping and planting design sometimes compete with scientific interests—with science now often taking second place.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/botanic-gardens] Some gardens are now heritage landscapes that are subject to constant demand for new exhibits and exemplary environmental management.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] A **charitable organization**, or **charity**, is an organization whose primary objectives are philanthropy and spreading social well-being (e.g. educational, religious or other activities serving the public interest or common good).
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] The legal definition of a charitable organization (and of charity) varies between countries and in some instances regions of the country.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] The regulation, the tax treatment, and the way in which charity law affects charitable organizations also vary.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Charitable organizations may not use any of their funds to profit individual persons or entities.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] However, some charitable organizations have come under scrutiny for spending a disproportionate amount of their income to pay the salaries of their leadership.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Financial figures (e.g. tax refunds, revenue from fundraising, revenue from the sale of goods and services or revenue from investment, and funds held in reserve) are indicators to assess the financial sustainability of a charity, especially to charity evaluators.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] This information can impact on a charity's reputation with donors and societies, and thus the charity's financial gains.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Charitable organizations often depend partly on donations from businesses.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Such donations to charitable organizations represent a major form of corporate philanthropy.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] To meet the exempt organizational test requirements, a charity has to be exclusively organized and operated, and to receive and pass the exemption test, a charitable organization must follow the public interest and all exempt income should be for the public interest.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] For example, in many countries of the Commonwealth, charitable organizations must demonstrate that they provide a public benefit.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Until the mid-18th century, charity was mainly distributed through religious structures (such as the English Poor Relief Act 1601), almshouses, and bequests from the rich.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Christianity, Judaism, and Islam incorporated significant charitable elements from their very beginnings, and *dāna* (alms-giving) has a long tradition in Hinduism, Jainism, Buddhism, and Sikhism.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Charities provided education, health, housing, and even prisons.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Almshouses were established throughout Europe in the Early Middle Ages to provide a place of residence for the poor, old, and distressed people; King Athelstan of England (reigned 924–939) founded the first recorded almshouse in York in the 10th century.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] During the Enlightenment era, charitable and philanthropic activity among voluntary associations and affluent benefactors became a widespread cultural practice.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Societies, gentlemen's clubs, and mutual associations began to flourish in England, with the upper classes increasingly adopting a philanthropic attitude toward the disadvantaged.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] In England, this new social activism led to the establishment of charitable organizations, which proliferated from the middle of the 18th century.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] This emerging upper-class trend for benevolence resulted in the incorporation of the first charitable organizations.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Appalled by the number of abandoned children living on the streets of London, Captain Thomas Coram set up the Foundling Hospital in 1741 to care for these unwanted orphans in Lamb's Conduit Fields, Bloomsbury.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] This institution, the world's first of its kind, served as the precedent for incorporated associational charities in general.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Another notable philanthropist of the Enlightenment era, Jonas Hanway, established The Marine Society in 1756 as the first seafarers' charity, aiming to aid the recruitment of men into the navy.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] By 1763, the Society had enlisted over 10,000 men, and an Act of Parliament incorporated it in 1772.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Hanway also played a key role in founding the Magdalen Hospital to rehabilitate prostitutes.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] These organizations were funded by subscriptions and operated as voluntary associations.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] They raised public awareness about their activities through the emerging popular press and generally enjoyed high social regard.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Some charities received state recognition in the form of a royal charter.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Charities also began to take on campaigning roles, championing causes and lobbying the government for legislative changes.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] This included organized campaigns against the mistreatment of animals and children, as well as the successful campaign in the early 19th century to end the slave trade throughout the British Empire and its extensive sphere of influence.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] The Enlightenment era also witnessed a growing philosophical debate between those advocating for state intervention and those believing that private charities should provide welfare.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] The political economist, Reverend Thomas Malthus (1766–1834), criticized poor relief for paupers on economic and moral grounds and proposed leaving charity entirely to the private sector.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] His views became highly influential and informed the Victorian *laissez-faire* attitude toward state intervention for the poor.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] During the 19th century, a profusion of charitable organizations emerged to alleviate the awful conditions of the working class in the slums.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] The Labourer's Friend Society, chaired by Lord Shaftesbury in the United Kingdom in 1830, aimed to improve working-class conditions.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] It promoted, for example, the allotment of land to laborers for "cottage husbandry", which later became the allotment movement.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] In 1844, it became the first Model Dwellings Company – one of a group of organizations that sought to improve the housing conditions of the working classes by building new homes for them, all the while receiving a competitive rate of return on any investment.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] This was one of the first housing associations, a philanthropic endeavor that flourished in the second half of the nineteenth century, brought about by the growth of the middle class.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Later associations included the Peabody Trust (originating in 1862) and the Guinness Trust (founded in 1890).
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] The principle of philanthropic intention with capitalist return was given the label "five percent philanthropy".
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] There was strong growth in municipal charities.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] The Brougham Commission led to the Municipal Corporations Act 1835, which reorganized multiple local charities by incorporating them into single entities under supervision from the local government.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Charities at the time, including the Charity Organization Society (established in 1869), tended to discriminate between the "deserving poor", who would be provided with suitable relief, and the "underserving" or "improvident poor", who was regarded as the cause of their woes due to their idleness.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Charities tended to oppose the provision of welfare by the state, due to the perceived demoralizing effect.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Although minimal state involvement was the dominant philosophy of the period, there was still significant government involvement in the form of statutory regulation and even limited funding.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Philanthropy became a very fashionable activity among the expanding middle classes in Britain and America.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Octavia Hill (1838–1912) and John Ruskin (1819–1900) were important forces behind the development of social housing, and Andrew Carnegie (1835–1919) exemplified the large-scale philanthropy of the newly rich in industrialized America.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] In *Gospel of Wealth* (1889), Carnegie wrote about the responsibilities of great wealth and the importance of social justice.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] He established public libraries throughout English-speaking countries and contributed large sums to schools and universities.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] A little over ten years after his retirement, Carnegie had given away over 90% of his fortune.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Charities that were founded during this time were often aligned with religion.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Towards the end of the 19th century, with the advent of the New Liberalism and the innovative work of Charles Booth in documenting working-class life in London, attitudes towards poverty began to change.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] This led to the first social liberal welfare reforms, including the provision of old age pensions and free school-meals.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] During the 20th century, charitable organizations such as Oxfam (established in 1947), Care International, and Amnesty International expanded greatly, becoming large, multinational non-governmental organizations with very large budgets.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] With the advent of the Internet, charitable organizations established a presence on online social media platforms and began initiatives such as cyber-based humanitarian crowdfunding, exemplified by platforms like GoFundMe.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] The definition of a charity in Australia is derived from English common law, originally from the Charitable Uses Act 1601, and then through several centuries of case law based upon it.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] In 2002, the federal government initiated an inquiry into the definition of a charity.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] The inquiry proposed a statutory definition of a charity, based on the principles developed through case law.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] This led to the *Charities Bill 2003*, which included limitations on the involvement of charities in political campaigning, an unwelcome departure from the case law as perceived by many charities.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] The government has appointed a Board of Taxation inquiry to consult with charities on the bill.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] However, due to widespread criticism from charities, the government abandoned the bill.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Subsequently, the government introduced the *Extension of Charitable Purpose Act 2004*.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] This act did not attempt to codify the definition of a charitable purpose but rather aimed to clarify that certain purposes were charitable, resolving legal doubts surrounding their charitable status.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Among these purposes were childcare, self-help groups, and closed/contemplative religious orders.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] To publicly raise funds, a charity in Australia must register in each Australian jurisdiction in which it intends to raise funds.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] For example, in Queensland, charities must register with the Queensland Office of Fair Trading.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Additionally, any charity fundraising online must obtain approval from every Australian jurisdiction that mandates such approval.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Currently, these jurisdictions include New South Wales, Queensland, Victoria, Tasmania, Western Australia, and the Australian Capital Territory.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Numerous Australian charities have appealed to federal, state, and territory governments to establish uniform legislation enabling charities registered in one state or territory to raise funds in all other Australian jurisdictions.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] The Australian Charities and Not-For-Profits Commission (ACNC) commenced operations in December 2012.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] It regulates approximately 56,000 non-profit organizations with tax-exempt status, along with around 600,000 other NPOs in total, seeking to standardize state-based fund-raising laws.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] A **Public Benevolent Institution** (PBI) is a specific type of charity with its primary purpose being to alleviate suffering in the community, whether due to poverty, sickness, or disability.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Examples of institutions that might qualify include hospices, providers of subsidized housing, and certain not-for-profit aged care services.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Charities in Canada need to be registered with the Charities Directorate of the Canada Revenue Agency.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Most French charities are registered under the statute of *loi d'association de 1901,* a type of legal entity for non-profit NGOs.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] This statute is extremely common in France for any type of group that wants to be institutionalized (sports clubs, book clubs, support groups...), as it is very easy to set up and requires very little documentation.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] However, for an organization under the statute of *loi 1901* to be considered a charity, it has to file with the authorities to come under the label of *"association d'utilité publique",* which means "NGO acting for the public interest".
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] This label gives the NGO some tax exemptions.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] In Hungary, charitable organizations are referred to as "public-benefit organizations" (Hungarian: *közhasznú szervezet*).
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] The term was introduced on 1 January 1997 through the Act on Public Benefit Organizations.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Under Indian law, legal entities such as charitable organizations, corporations, and managing bodies have been given the status of "legal persons" with legal rights, such as the right to sue and be sued, and the right to own and transfer property.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Indian charitable organizations with this status include Sir Ratan Tata Trust.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] In Ireland, the Charities Act (2009) legislated the establishment of a "Charities Regulatory Authority", and the Charities Regulator was subsequently created via a ministerial order in 2014.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] This was the first legal framework for charity registration in Ireland.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] The Charities Regulator maintains a database of organizations that have been granted charitable tax exemption—a list previously maintained by the Revenue Commissioners.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Such organizations would have a CHY number from the Revenue Commissioners, a CRO number from the Companies Registration Office, and a charity number from the Charities Regulator.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] The Irish Nonprofits Database was created by Irish Nonprofits Knowledge Exchange (INKEx) to serve as a repository for regulatory and voluntarily disclosed information about Irish public benefit nonprofits.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Charitable organizations in Nigeria are registerable under "Part C" of the Companies and Allied Matters Act, 2020.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Under the law, the Corporate Affairs Commission, Nigeria, being the official Nigerian Corporate Registry, is empowered to maintain and regulate the formation, operation, and dissolution of charitable organizations in Nigeria.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Charitable organizations in Nigeria are exempted under §25(c) of the Companies Income Tax Act (CITA) Cap.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] C21 LFN 2004 (as amended), which exempts from income tax corporate organizations engaged wholly in ecclesiastical, charitable, or educational activities.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Similarly, §3 of the Value Added Tax Act (VATA) Cap.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] V1 LFN 2004 (as amended), and the 1st Schedule to the VATA on exempted Goods and Services goods zero-rates goods and services purchased by any ecclesiastical, charitable, or educational institutions in furtherance of their charitable mandates.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] A public benefit organization (Polish: *organizacja pożytku publicznego*, often abbreviated as OPP) is a term used in Polish law.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] It was introduced on 1 January 2004 by the statute on public good activity and volunteering.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Charitable organizations of public good are allowed to receive 1.5% of income tax from individuals, making them "tax-deductible organizations".
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] To receive such status, an organization has to be a non-governmental organization, with political parties and trade unions not qualifying.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] The organization must also be involved in specific activities related to the public good as described by the law, and it should demonstrate sufficient transparency in its activities, governance, and finances.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Moreover, data has shown that this evidence is pertinent and sensible.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Polish charitable organizations with this status include Związek Harcerstwa Polskiego, the Great Orchestra of Christmas Charity, KARTA Center, the Institute of Public Affairs, the Silesian Fantasy Club, the Polish Historical Society, and the Polish chapter of the Wikimedia Foundation.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] The legal framework in Singapore is regulated by the Singapore Charities Act (Chapter 37).
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Charities in Singapore must be registered with the Charities Directorate of the Ministry of Community Development, Youth and Sports.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] One can also find specific organizations that are members of the National Council of Social Service (NCSS), which is operated by the Ministry of Social and Family Development.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] The legislation governing charitable activities and the process of obtaining charitable organization status is regulated by Ukraine's Civil Code and the Law of Ukraine on Charitable Activities and Charitable Organizations.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] The Ministry of Justice of Ukraine is the main registration authority for charitable organization registration and constitution.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Individuals and legal entities, except for public authorities and local governments, can be the founders of charitable organizations.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Charitable societies and charitable foundations may have, in addition to founders, other participants who have joined them as prescribed by the charters of such charitable associations or charitable foundations.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Aliens (non-Ukrainian citizens and legal entities, corporations, or non-governmental organizations) can be the founders and members of philanthropic organizations in Ukraine.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] All funds received by a charitable organization and used for charitable purposes are exempt from taxation, but obtaining non-profit status from the tax authority is necessary.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Legalization is required for international charitable funds to operate in Ukraine.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Charity law in the UK varies between (i) England and Wales, (ii) Scotland and (iii) Northern Ireland, but the fundamental principles are the same.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Most organizations that are charities are required to be registered with the appropriate regulator for their jurisdiction, but significant exceptions apply so that many organizations are *bona fide* charities but do not appear on a public register.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] The registers are maintained by the Charity Commission for England and Wales and by the Office of the Scottish Charity Regulator for Scotland.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] The Charity Commission for Northern Ireland maintains a register of charities that have completed formal registration (see below).
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Organizations applying must meet the specific legal requirements summarized below, have filing requirements with their regulator, and are subject to inspection or other forms of review.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] The oldest charity in the UK is The King's School, Canterbury, established in 597 AD.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Charitable organizations, including charitable trusts, are eligible for a complex set of reliefs and exemptions from taxation in the UK.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] These include reliefs and exemptions in relation to income tax, capital gains tax, inheritance tax, stamp duty land tax, and value added tax.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] These tax exemptions have led to criticisms that private schools are able to use charitable status as a tax avoidance technique rather than offering a genuine charitable good.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Since 1 January 2025, private school fees have been subject to the standard rate of VAT (20%); this measure was brought in by the Starmer ministry.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] The Transparency of Lobbying, Non-party Campaigning and Trade Union Administration Act 2014 subjects charities to regulation by the Electoral Commission in the run-up to a general election.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] (b) falls to be subject to the control of the High Court in the exercise of its jurisdiction with respect to charities.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] 13. other purposes currently recognized as charitable and any new charitable purposes which are similar to another charitable purpose.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] A charity must also provide a public benefit.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] To receive tax relief, a charity must apply to HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC), which verifies whether the requirements are satisfied.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] In *Commissioners for Special Purposes of Income Tax v.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] 4. other purposes considered beneficial to the community.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Charities in England and Wales—such as Age UK, the Royal Society for the Protection of Birds (RSPB) and the Royal Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals (RSPCA) – must comply with the 2011 Act regulating matters such as charity reports and accounts and fundraising.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] The unincorporated association is the most common form of organization within the voluntary sector in England and Wales.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] This is essentially a contractual arrangement between individuals who have agreed to come together to form an organization for a particular purpose.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] An unincorporated association will normally have a constitution or set of rules as its governing document, which will deal with matters such as the appointment of office bearers and the rules governing membership.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] The organization is not, however, a separate legal entity, so it cannot initiate legal action, borrow money, or enter into contracts in its own name.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Its officers can be personally liable if the charity is sued or has debts.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] A trust is essentially a relationship among three parties: the donor of some assets, the trustees who hold the assets, and the beneficiaries (those eligible to benefit from the charity).
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] When the trust has charitable purposes and is a charity, the trust is known as a charitable trust.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] The governing document is the trust deed or declaration of trust, which comes into operation once signed by all the trustees.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] The main disadvantage of a trust is that, like an unincorporated association, it lacks a separate legal entity, and the trustees must themselves own property and enter into contracts.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] The trustees are also liable if the charity is sued or incurs liability.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] A company limited by guarantee is a private limited company where members' liability is limited.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] A guarantee company does not have a share capital, but instead has members who are guarantors rather than shareholders.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] If the company is wound up, the members agree to pay a nominal sum, which can be as little as £1.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] A company limited by guarantee is a useful structure for a charity where trustees need limited liability protection.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Moreover, the charity has legal personality and can enter into contracts, such as employment contracts, in its own name.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] A small number of charities are incorporated by royal charter, a document that creates a corporation with legal personality (or, in some cases, transforms a charity incorporated as a company into a charity incorporated by royal charter).
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] The charter must be approved by the Privy Council before receiving royal assent.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] While the nature of the charity will vary depending on the clauses enacted, a royal charter generally offers a charity the same limited liability as a company and the ability to enter into contracts.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] The Charities Act 2006 introduced a new legal form of incorporation designed specifically for charities—the charitable incorporated organization (CIO)—with powers similar to a company but without the need to register as a company.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Becoming a CIO was only made possible in 2013, with staggered introduction dates, with the charities with the highest turnover eligible first.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] The term *foundation* is not commonly used in England and Wales.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Occasionally, a charity will use the word as part of its name (e.g., British Heart Foundation), but this has no legal significance and provides no information about the charity's work or legal structure.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] The organization's structure will fall into one of the types described above.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Charitable organizations with an income of over £5,000 and subject to the law of England and Wales must register with the Charity Commission for England and Wales, unless they are an "exempt" or "excepted" charity.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] For companies, the law of England and Wales will usually apply if the company itself is registered in England and Wales.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] In other cases, if the governing document does not specify, the law that applies will be the one most connected with the organization.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] When an organization's income does not exceed £5,000, it cannot register as a charity with the Charity Commission for England and Wales, unless registered as a charitable incorporated organisation, in which case there is no minimum annual income.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] With the increase in the mandatory registration level to £5,000 by The Charities Act 2006, smaller charities can rely on HMRC recognition to demonstrate their charitable purpose and confirm their not-for-profit principles.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Churches with an annual income of less than £100,000 need not register.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Some charities, referred to as exempt charities, are not required to register with the Charity Commission and are not subject to its supervisory powers.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] These charities include most universities and national museums, as well as some other educational institutions.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Other charities are excepted from the need to register but are still subject to the supervision of the Charity Commission.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] The regulations on excepted charities were changed by the Charities Act 2006.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Many excepted charities are religious charities.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] The Charity Commission for Northern Ireland was established in 2009 and has received the names and details of over 7,000 organizations in Northern Ireland that have previously been granted charitable status for tax purposes (the "deemed list").
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Compulsory registration of organizations from the deemed list began in December 2013, and it is expected to take three to four years to complete.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] The new Register of Charities is publicly available on the CCNI website and contains the details of those organizations that have so far been confirmed by the commission to exist for charitable purposes and the public benefit.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] The Commission estimates that between 5,000 and 11,500 charitable organizations need to be formally registered in total.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] The approximately 24,000 charities in Scotland are registered with the Office of the Scottish Charity Regulator (OSCR), which also maintains a register of charities online.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] In the United States, a charitable organization is an organization operated for purposes that are beneficial to the public interest.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] There are different types of charitable organizations.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Every U.S. and foreign charity that qualifies as tax-exempt under Section 501(c)(3) of the Internal Revenue Code (IRC) is considered a "private foundation" unless it demonstrates to the Internal Revenue Service (IRS) that it falls into another category.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Generally, any organization that is not a private foundation (i.e., it qualifies as something else) is usually a public charity as described in Section 509(a) of the IRC.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] In addition, a private foundation usually derives its principal funding from an individual, family, corporation, or some other single source, and it is more often than not a grantmaker that does not solicit funds from the public.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] In contrast, a foundation or public charity generally receives grants from individuals, government, and private foundations.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] While some public charities engage in grantmaking activities, most conduct direct service or other tax-exempt activities.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Foundations that are generally grantmakers (i.e., they use their endowment to make grants to other organizations, which in turn carry out the goals of the foundation indirectly) are usually called "grantmaker" or "non-operating" foundations.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] The requirements and procedures for forming charitable organizations vary from state to state, as do the registration and filing requirements for charitable organizations that conduct charitable activities, solicit charitable contributions, or hire professional fundraisers.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] In practice, the detailed definition of a "charitable organization" is determined by the requirements of state law where the charitable organization operates, and the requirements for federal tax relief by the IRS.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Resources exist to provide information, including rankings, of US charities.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Federal tax law provides tax benefits to nonprofit organizations recognized as exempt from federal income tax under section 501(c)(3) of the IRC.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] The benefits of 501(c)(3) status include exemption from federal income tax as well as eligibility to receive tax-deductible charitable contributions.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] In 2017, there were a total of $281.86 billion in tax-deductible donations by individuals.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] To qualify for 501(c)(3) status, most organizations must apply to the IRS for such status.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Several requirements must be met for a charitable organization to obtain 501(c)(3) status.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] These include the organization being organized as a corporation, trust, or unincorporated association.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] The organization's organizing document (such as the articles of incorporation, trust documents, or articles of association) must limit its purposes to being charitable and permanently dedicate its assets to charitable purposes.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] The organization must refrain from undertaking a number of other activities, such as participating in the political campaigns of candidates for local, state, or federal office.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Additionally, the organization must ensure that its earnings do not benefit any individual.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Most tax-exempt organizations are required to file annual financial reports (IRS Form 990) at the state and federal level.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] A tax-exempt organization's Form 990 and some other forms are required to be made available for public scrutiny.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Economist Robert Reich criticized the practice of billionaires giving some of their money to charity, calling it mostly "self-serving rubbish".
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Charity fraud, also known as a donation scam, is the act of using deception to obtain money from people who believe they are donating to a charity.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Often, individuals or groups will present false information claiming to be a charity or associated with one, and then ask potential donors for contributions to this non-existent charity.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Charity fraud encompasses not only fictitious charities but also deceptive business practices.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] These deceitful acts by businesses may involve accepting donations without using the funds for their intended purposes or soliciting funds under false pretenses of need.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charitable-organization] Charity regulators oversee the registration, compliance, and governance of charitable organizations within their respective jurisdictions.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] The **Charity Commission for England and Wales** (Welsh: *Comisiwn Elusennau Cymru a Lloegr*) is the statutory regulator of registered charities in England and Wales.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] It maintains the public register of charities and oversees compliance with charity law.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] The Commission is a non-ministerial department of His Majesty's Government that regulates registered charities in England and Wales and maintains the **Central Register of Charities**.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] Its counterparts in Scotland and Northern Ireland are the Office of the Scottish Charity Regulator and the Charity Commission for Northern Ireland.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] The commission has four sites in London, Taunton, Liverpool and Newport.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] Its website lists the latest annual reports submitted by charities in England and Wales.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] During the financial year 2022–2023, the Commission regulated £88 billion of charity income and £85 billion of charity spend.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] To establish a charity, an organisation must first find at least three trustees who will be responsible for the general control and management of the administration of the charity.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] The organisation needs to have a charitable purpose that helps the public.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] Afterwards, the administration must select an official name and decide on a structure for the charity that will impact aspects such as who runs the charity and how it is run.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] Subsequently, the creation of a governing document that explains how the charity is run is required.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] Finally, an electronic application must be completed if the charity’s income is at £5,000 per year, or it is a charitable incorporated organisation (CIO).
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] There are different rules for creating a charity in Scotland and Northern Ireland.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] Some charities are not subject to regulation by or registration with the Charity Commission, because they are already regulated by another body, and are known as exempt charities.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] Most exempt charities are listed in Schedule 3 to the Charities Act 2011, but some charities are made exempt by other acts.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] However exempt charities must still comply with charity law and may approach the Charity Commission for advice.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] Some charities are 'excepted' from charity registration.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] This means they do not have to register or submit annual returns, but are in all other respects subject to regulation by the Charity Commission.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] Registration of a charity in England and Wales does not endow that status elsewhere, thus further registration has to be made before operating in Scotland or Northern Ireland.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] Charities in Scotland are regulated by the Office of the Scottish Charity Regulator.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] In Northern Ireland the Charity Commission for Northern Ireland was established in 2009 to replace earlier regulation by the Voluntary and Community Unit of the Department for Social Development, part of the Northern Ireland Executive.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] The principles of good governance, to be followed by charities in order for them to be able to achieve and maintain charitable status, are laid down in the Charity Governance Code, published by the Charity Governance Code Steering Group.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] There are two separate codes for small and large charities.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] The Charity Commission is not part of the Charity Governance Code Steering Group; it is only an observer, to ensure impartiality.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] Depending on how serious the complaint is, the Charity Commission will either recommend procedural improvements, require the expulsion of unsuitable trustees, or remove the organisation's charitable status altogether.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] The Charities Act 2006 requires the Commission to be operationally independent of ministerial influence or control.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] Members of the commission, including the chair, are appointed by the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] The Finance Act 2010 extended charitable tax benefits (for example Gift Aid) to charities within EU member states, Norway and Iceland, rather than those just inside the UK.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] In 2016, following the Olive Cooke scandal, British fundraising regulations were reviewed.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] This led to the establishment of the Fundraising Regulator.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] The Fundraising Regulator is an independent oversight body without statutory authority.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] It defines and promotes fundraising standards, investigates cases, addresses public complaints about fundraising practices, and operates a fundraising preference service that allows the public to control how charities contact them.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] The commission carries out general monitoring of charities as part of its regular casework.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] In serious cases of abuse and regulatory concern, the commission has powers outlined in the Charities Acts to conduct statutory investigations.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] Before taking the decision to open a statutory inquiry, it will take the approach set out in its Regulatory and Risk framework.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] The commission, therefore, began around 2007 to carry out an intermediate form of action described as regulatory compliance investigations.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] In 2010 it opened over 140 of these cases, compared to just three full statutory investigations.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] However, the legality of these actions was debatable as they lacked a statutory basis.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] A high-profile example was the commission's report into The Atlantic Bridge, after which that body was dissolved in September 2011.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] The commission announced in October 2011, in the context of cost-cutting and a re-focussing of its activities, that it would no longer carry out regulatory compliance investigations.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] In 2012, the commission refused to grant charitable status to Plymouth Brethren Christian Church, stating that it was unclear whether the body's aims were compatible with the requirement for charities to have a public benefit.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] The commission stated that this was called into doubt as a result of the "exclusivity" of the body.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] The decision was discussed at a session of the Public Accounts Committee, during which MP Charlie Elphicke accused the commission of being "committed to the suppression of religion".
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] The decision was later reversed by the Commission.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] Between 2022 and 2023, the commission removed 4,146 charities from the register and concluded 5,726 regulatory action cases (includes 68 statutory inquiries).
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] Prior to the 1840s, a body of commissioners had been established by the Statute of Charitable Uses 1601 (43 Eliz.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] The Charity Commission was first established by the Charitable Trusts Act 1853.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] There had been several attempts at reforming charities before that which had been opposed by various interest groups including the church, the courts, the companies, and the universities.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] The power of the commission was strengthened by amendments to the act in 1855, 1860, and 1862.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] The Charity Commission was substantially reconstituted by the Charities Act 1960 (8 & 9 Eliz.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] 58), which replaced the Charitable Trusts Acts (1853-1891).
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] This introduced new duties to determine charitable status, and to maintain a public register of charities.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] The commission was criticised after the Aberfan disaster in 1966 for its intransigence and decisions on what it allowed money from the disaster fund to be spent on.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] It sanctioned the use of £150,000 to remove remaining spoil tips from the area after the National Coal Board refused to pay for the work.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] It also proposed asking parents 'exactly how close were you to your child?'; those found not to have been close to their children would not be compensated.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] The Charities Act 2006 established its current structure and name.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] As of 31 March 2015 the commission had 288 employees and 19 agency staff in post.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] The Olive Cooke case, involving a 92-year-old poppy seller who allegedly committed suicide due to overwhelming requests for donations from charities, sparked widespread public fear and media attention across England and Wales.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] This scandal prompted a review of the self-regulation of fundraising practices in England and Wales, as well as Scotland, subsequently leading to the introduction of self-regulatory reforms in both jurisdictions.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] Orlando Fraser was appointed as chair of the Charity Commission by the Secretary of State on a three-year term commencing from 25 April 2022.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] This appointment was not without controversy, including the refusal of the Digital, Culture, Media and Sports Committee to endorse the appointment.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] Chief charity commissioner – prior to restructuring in 2006, the equivalent of the chair was the chief charity commissioner.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Charles is the eldest son of Queen Elizabeth II and Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] He was born during the reign of his maternal grandfather, King George VI, and became heir apparent following his mother's accession in 1952.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] He was created Prince of Wales in 1958 and his investiture was held in 1969.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] He was educated at Cheam School and Gordonstoun, and later spent six months at the Timbertop campus of Geelong Grammar School in Victoria, Australia.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] After completing a history degree at the University of Cambridge, he served in the Royal Air Force and the Royal Navy from 1971 to 1976.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] He married Lady Diana Spencer in 1981 and they had two sons, William and Harry.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Charles and Diana divorced in 1996 after years of estrangement and well-publicised extramarital affairs.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Diana died the following year from injuries sustained in a car crash.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In 2005, Charles married his long-time partner, Camilla Parker Bowles.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] As heir apparent, Charles undertook official duties and engagements on behalf of his mother and represented the United Kingdom on visits abroad.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] He founded the Prince's Trust in 1976, sponsored the Prince's Charities and became patron or president of more than 800 other charities and organisations.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] He advocated for the conservation of historic buildings and the importance of traditional architecture in society, and in that vein generated the experimental new town of Poundbury.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] An environmentalist, Charles supported organic farming and action to address climate change during his time as manager of the Duchy of Cornwall estates, earning him awards and recognition.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] He has also been a prominent critic of genetically modified food, and has drawn scrutiny for his support of alternative medicine.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] He has authored or co-authored 17 books.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Charles became king upon his mother's death in 2022.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] At the age of 73 he was the oldest person to accede to the British throne, after having been the longest-serving heir apparent and Prince of Wales in British history.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Significant events in his reign have included his coronation in 2023, his cancer diagnosis in 2024 which temporarily suspended planned public engagements, and the removal of his brother Andrew's remaining titles, styles, and honours in 2025.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Charles was born at 9:14 pm on 14 November 1948 by caesarean section at Buckingham Palace, during the reign of his maternal grandfather, King George VI.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] He was the first child of Princess Elizabeth, Duchess of Edinburgh (later Queen Elizabeth II), and Philip, Duke of Edinburgh.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] He was christened Charles Philip Arthur George on 15 December in the Music Room at Buckingham Palace by the archbishop of Canterbury, Geoffrey Fisher.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] He has three younger siblings: Anne (born 1950), Andrew (born 1960), and Edward (born 1964).
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] George VI died on 6 February 1952, after which Charles's mother acceded to the throne as Elizabeth II and he became heir apparent.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Under a charter issued by Edward III in 1337, and as the monarch's eldest son, he automatically assumed the titles of Duke of Cornwall and, in the Scottish peerage, Duke of Rothesay, Earl of Carrick, Baron of Renfrew, Lord of the Isles, and Prince and Great Steward of Scotland.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] He attended his mother's coronation at Westminster Abbey on 2 June 1953.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] When Charles was five, Catherine Peebles was appointed as his governess to oversee his education at Buckingham Palace.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] He began attending Hill House School in West London in November 1956, becoming the first heir apparent to be educated at a school rather than by private tutors.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] He did not receive preferential treatment from the school's founder and headmaster, Stuart Townend, who encouraged the Queen to have Charles train in football, noting that boys on the pitch were never deferential to anyone.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Charles later attended two of his father's former schools: Cheam School in Hampshire from 1958, followed by Gordonstoun in Moray, where he began classes in April 1962.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] He became patron of Gordonstoun in May 2024.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Jonathan Dimbleby's authorised 1994 biography described Elizabeth and Philip as physically and emotionally distant parents, and criticised Philip for disregarding Charles's sensitive nature, including insisting that Charles attend Gordonstoun, where he was bullied.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Although Charles reportedly referred to the school as "Colditz in kilts", he later praised Gordonstoun for teaching him "a great deal about myself and my own abilities and disabilities".
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In a 1975 interview Charles said he was "glad" to have attended the school and that its "toughness" had been "much exaggerated".
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In 1966, Charles spent two terms at the Timbertop campus of Geelong Grammar School in Victoria, Australia, during which he visited Papua New Guinea on a school trip with his history tutor, Michael Collins Persse.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Charles later described his time at Timbertop as the most enjoyable part of his education.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] On returning to Gordonstoun, he became head boy, and left in 1967 with six GCE O-levels and two A-levels in history and French, at grades B and C respectively.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Reflecting on his schooling, Charles later remarked that he "didn't enjoy school as much as I might have", adding that he was "happier at home than anywhere else".
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Breaking royal tradition, Charles proceeded directly to university after completing his A‑levels rather than joining the British Armed Forces.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In October 1967, he was admitted to the University of Cambridge to study archaeology and anthropology for the first part of the Tripos at Trinity College, Cambridge, later switching to history.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] During his second year he spent one term at the University College of Wales in Aberystwyth, studying Welsh history and Welsh language.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Charles became the first British heir apparent to earn a university degree, graduating from Cambridge in June 1970 with a Bachelor of Arts (BA) degree with lower second-class honours (2:2).
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Following standard practice, his BA was promoted to a Master of Arts (MA Cantab) in August 1975.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Charles was created Prince of Wales and Earl of Chester on 26 July 1958, although his investiture did not take place until 1 July 1969, when he was crowned by his mother in a televised ceremony at Caernarfon Castle.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] The event was controversial in Wales amid rising Welsh nationalist sentiment.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] He took his seat in the House of Lords the following year, delivering his maiden speech on 13 June 1974, the first royal to speak from the floor since the future Edward VII in 1884.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Charles increasingly undertook public duties, founding the Prince's Trust in 1976 and travelling to the United States in 1981.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In the mid-1970s he expressed interest in serving as Governor-General of Australia, following a suggestion by the Australian prime minister, Malcolm Fraser.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] The proposal was ultimately abandoned owing to a lack of public enthusiasm.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Charles served in the Royal Air Force (RAF) and the Royal Navy during the 1970s.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] His military training began in 1969, in his second year at Cambridge, when he joined the Cambridge University Air Squadron and learned to fly the Chipmunk.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] He was presented with his RAF wings in August 1971.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] After the passing-out parade that September, Charles embarked on a naval career and undertook a six-week course at the Royal Naval College, Dartmouth.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] He subsequently served from 1971 to 1972 on the guided-missile destroyer HMS *Norfolk*, and on the frigates HMS *Minerva* from 1972 to 1973 and HMS *Jupiter* in 1974.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] That same year he qualified as a helicopter pilot at RNAS Yeovilton, and during his helicopter training completed commando instruction at the Commando Training Centre Royal Marines at Lympstone.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Charles then joined 845 Naval Air Squadron, a Royal Marines air support unit of the Fleet Air Arm, serving as a pilot aboard HMS *Hermes* and flying the Royal Marines commando variant of the Westland Wessex helicopter.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Charles spent his final ten months of active naval service commanding the coastal minehunter HMS *Bronington*, beginning on 9 February 1976.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] He retired from active service later that year with the rank of Commander.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Two years later he undertook the parachute training course at RAF Brize Norton, having been appointed colonel-in-chief of the Parachute Regiment in 1977, and was a member of Parachute Course 841a.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Charles gave up flying after crash-landing a BAe 146 in Islay in 1994, when, as a passenger invited to fly the aircraft, he was at the controls; a board of inquiry found the crew negligent.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In his youth, Charles was romantically linked to several women.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] His girlfriends included Georgiana Russell, the daughter of Sir John Russell, who was the British ambassador to Spain; Lady Jane Wellesley; Davina Sheffield; Lady Sarah Spencer; and Camilla Shand, who later became his second wife.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Charles's great-uncle Lord Mountbatten advised him to "sow his wild oats and have as many affairs as he can before settling down", but, for a wife, he "should choose a suitable, attractive, and sweet-charactered girl before she has met anyone else she might fall for ...
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] It is disturbing for women to have experiences if they have to remain on a pedestal after marriage".
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Early in 1974, Mountbatten began corresponding with 25-year-old Charles about a potential marriage to his granddaughter, Amanda Knatchbull.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Charles wrote to Amanda's mother, Lady Brabourne, who was also his godmother, expressing interest in her daughter.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Lady Brabourne replied approvingly, but suggested that a courtship with a 16-year-old was premature.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Four years later, Mountbatten arranged for Amanda and himself to accompany Charles on his 1980 visit to India.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Both fathers, however, objected: Prince Philip feared that his famous uncle would eclipse Charles, while Lord Brabourne warned that a joint visit would concentrate media attention on the cousins before they could decide whether to become a couple.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In August 1979, before Charles was due to depart alone for India, Mountbatten was assassinated by the Provisional Irish Republican Army.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] When Charles returned, he proposed to Amanda.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] But in addition to her grandfather, she had lost her paternal grandmother and younger brother in the bomb attack, and was now reluctant to join the royal family.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Charles first met Lady Diana Spencer in 1977, while he was visiting her home, Althorp.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] He was then the companion of her elder sister Sarah and did not consider Diana romantically until mid-1980.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] While Charles and Diana were sitting together on a bale of hay at a friend's barbecue in July, she mentioned that he had looked forlorn and in need of care at the funeral of Lord Mountbatten.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Soon, according to Dimbleby, "without any apparent surge in feeling, he began to think seriously of her as a potential bride" and she accompanied him on visits to Balmoral Castle and Sandringham House.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Charles's cousin Norton Knatchbull and his wife told Charles that Diana appeared awestruck by his position and that he did not seem to be in love with her.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Meanwhile, the couple's continuing courtship attracted intense attention from the press and paparazzi.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] He proposed to Diana in February 1981, with their engagement becoming official on 24 February; the wedding took place at St Paul's Cathedral on 29 July.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Upon his marriage, Charles reduced his voluntary tax contribution from the profits of the Duchy of Cornwall from 50 per cent to 25 per cent.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] The couple lived at Kensington Palace and Highgrove House, near Tetbury, and had two children: William, in 1982, and Harry, in 1984.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] As of 2025, Charles has an estranged relationship with his son Harry, who relinquished his royal family obligations and moved to the United States in 2020.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Within five years, the marriage was in trouble due to the couple's incompatibility and near 13-year age difference.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In 1986 Charles had fully resumed his affair with former girlfriend, Camilla Parker Bowles.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Diana later commenced a relationship with Major James Hewitt, the family's former riding instructor.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Charles and Diana's evident discomfort in each other's company led to them being dubbed "The Glums" by the press.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Diana exposed Charles's affair with Parker Bowles in a book by Andrew Morton, *Diana: Her True Story*.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Audio tapes of her own extramarital flirtations also surfaced, as did persistent suggestions that Hewitt is Prince Harry's father, based on a physical similarity between Hewitt and Harry.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] However, Harry had already been born by the time Diana's affair with Hewitt began.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In December 1992, the British prime minister, John Major, announced the couple's legal separation in the House of Commons.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Early the following year, the British press published transcripts of a passionate, bugged telephone conversation between Charles and Parker Bowles that had taken place in 1989, which was dubbed "Tampongate" and "Camillagate".
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Charles subsequently sought public understanding in a television film with Dimbleby, *Charles: The Private Man, the Public Role*, broadcast in June 1994.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In an interview in the film, Charles confirmed his own extramarital affair with Parker Bowles, saying that he had rekindled their association in 1986, only after his marriage to Diana had "irretrievably broken down".
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] This was followed by Diana's own admission of marital troubles in an interview on the BBC current affairs programme *Panorama*, broadcast in November 1995.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Referring to Charles's relationship with Parker Bowles, she said, "well, there were three of us in this marriage.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] So, it was a bit crowded." She also expressed doubt about her husband's suitability for kingship.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Charles and Diana divorced on 28 August 1996, after being advised by the Queen in December 1995 to end the marriage.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] The couple shared custody of their children.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Diana died following a car crash in Paris on 31 August 1997.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Charles flew to Paris with Diana's sisters to accompany her body back to Britain.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In 2003, Diana's butler Paul Burrell published a note that he claimed had been written by Diana in 1995, in which there were allegations that Charles was "planning 'an accident' in [Diana's] car, brake failure and serious head injury", so that he could remarry.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] She had allegedly expressed similar concerns in October 1995 to Lord Mishcon, her solicitor, that "reliable sources" had told her "that she and Camilla would be put aside" for Charles to marry Tiggy Legge-Bourke.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] When questioned by the Metropolitan Police inquiry team as a part of Operation Paget, Charles told the authorities that he did not know about his former wife's note from 1995 and could not understand why she had those feelings.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] The allegations were later revealed to have been among the smears spread by journalist Martin Bashir to secure an interview with Diana for the BBC.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Because Charles and Parker Bowles were romantically involved periodically, both before and during their respective first marriages, their relationship received criticism from the public and the media.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Following both of their divorces, Charles declared his relationship with Parker Bowles was "non-negotiable" and appointed Mark Bolland to enhance Parker Bowles's public profile.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In 2003, Parker Bowles moved into Charles's official residence, Clarence House and she accompanied Charles on almost all of his official events, including the annual Highland Games in Scotland.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Former Archbishop of Canterbury, George Carey, told *The Times* that Charles and Parker Bowles should marry, "He is heir to the throne and he loves her.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] The natural thing is that they should get married." Their engagement was announced on 10 February 2005.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] The Queen's consent to the marriage – as required by the Royal Marriages Act 1772 – was recorded in a Privy Council meeting on 2 March.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In Canada, the Department of Justice determined the consent of the Queen's Privy Council for Canada was not required, as the union would not produce any heirs to the Canadian throne.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Charles was the only member of the royal family to have a civil, rather than a church, wedding in England.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] British government documents from the 1950s and 1960s, published by the BBC, stated that such a marriage was illegal; these claims were dismissed by Charles's spokesman and explained by the sitting government to have been repealed by the Registration Service Act 1953.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] The union was scheduled to take place in a civil ceremony at Windsor Castle, with a subsequent religious blessing at the castle's St George's Chapel.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] The wedding venue was changed to Windsor Guildhall after it was realised a civil marriage at Windsor Castle would oblige the venue to be available to anyone who wished to be married there.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Four days before the event, it was postponed from the originally scheduled date of 8 April until the following day in order to allow Charles and some of the invited dignitaries to attend the funeral of Pope John Paul II.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Charles's parents did not attend the marriage ceremony; the Queen's reluctance to attend possibly arose from her position as Supreme Governor of the Church of England.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] However, his parents did attend the service of blessing and held a reception for the newlyweds at Windsor Castle.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] The blessing by Archbishop of Canterbury Rowan Williams was televised.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Since their marriage in 2005, Charles has paid tribute to Camilla repeatedly in public letters, speeches and interviews, thanking her for "steadfast support" and referring to her as "my darling wife".
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In 1965, Charles undertook his first public engagement by attending a student garden party at the Palace of Holyroodhouse.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] During his time as Prince of Wales, he undertook official duties on behalf of the Queen, completing 10,934 engagements between 2002 and 2022.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] He officiated at investitures and attended the funerals of foreign dignitaries.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Charles made regular tours of Wales, fulfilling a week of engagements each summer, and attending important national occasions, such as opening the Senedd.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] The six trustees of the Royal Collection Trust met three times a year under his chairmanship.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Charles also represented his mother at the independence celebrations in Fiji in 1970, The Bahamas in 1973, Papua New Guinea in 1975, Zimbabwe in 1980 and Brunei in 1984.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In 1983, a man named Christopher John Lewis, who had fired a shot with a .22 rifle at the Queen in 1981, attempted to escape a psychiatric hospital in order to assassinate Charles, who was visiting New Zealand with Diana and William.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] While Charles was visiting Australia on Australia Day in January 1994, David Kang fired two shots at him from a starting pistol in protest against the treatment of several hundred Cambodian asylum-seekers held in detention camps.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In 1995 Charles became the first member of the royal family to visit the Republic of Ireland in an official capacity.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In 1997 he represented the Queen at the Hong Kong handover ceremony.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] At the funeral of Pope John Paul II in 2005, Charles caused controversy when he shook hands with Zimbabwean president Robert Mugabe, who had been seated next to him.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Charles's office subsequently released a statement saying that he could not avoid shaking Mugabe's hand and that he "finds the current Zimbabwean regime abhorrent".
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Charles represented the Queen at the opening ceremony of the 2010 Commonwealth Games in Delhi, India.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In November 2010 he and Camilla were indirectly involved in student protests when their car was attacked by protesters.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In November 2013 he represented the Queen for the first time at a Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting, in Colombo, Sri Lanka.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Charles and Camilla made their first joint trip to the Republic of Ireland in May 2015.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] The British Embassy called the trip an important step in "promoting peace and reconciliation".
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] During the trip, he shook hands in Galway with Gerry Adams, leader of Sinn Féin and widely believed to be the leader of the IRA, the militant group that had assassinated Lord Mountbatten in 1979.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] The event was described by the media as a "historic handshake" and a "significant moment for Anglo-Irish relations".
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Commonwealth heads of government decided at their 2018 meeting that Charles would be the next Head of the Commonwealth after the Queen.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] The head is chosen and therefore not hereditary.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In March 2019, at the request of the British government, Charles and Camilla went on an official tour of Cuba, making them the first British royals to visit the country.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] The tour was seen as an effort to form a closer relationship between Cuba and the United Kingdom.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Charles contracted COVID-19 during the pandemic in March 2020.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Several newspapers were critical that Charles and Camilla were tested promptly at a time when many National Health Service doctors, nurses and patients had been unable to be tested expeditiously.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] He tested positive for COVID-19 for a second time in February 2022.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] He and Camilla, who also tested positive, had received doses of a COVID-19 vaccine in February 2021.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Charles attended the November 2021 ceremonies to mark Barbados's transition into a parliamentary republic, abolishing the position of monarch of Barbados.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] He was invited by Prime Minister Mia Mottley as the future Head of the Commonwealth; it was the first time that a member of the royal family attended the transition of a realm to a republic.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In May of the following year, Charles attended the State Opening of the British Parliament, delivering the Queen's Speech on behalf of his mother, as a counsellor of state.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Charles acceded to the British throne on his mother's death on 8 September 2022.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] He was the longest-serving British heir apparent, having surpassed Edward VII's record of 59 years on 20 April 2011.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Charles was the oldest person to succeed to the British throne, at the age of 73, surpassing the previous record holder, William IV, who was 64 when he became king in 1830.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Charles gave his first speech to the nation at 6 pm on 9 September, in which he paid tribute to his mother and announced the appointment of his elder son, William, as Prince of Wales.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] The following day, the Accession Council publicly proclaimed Charles as king, the ceremony being televised for the first time.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Attendees included Queen Camilla, Prince William and the British prime minister, Liz Truss, along with her six living predecessors.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] The proclamation was also read out by local authorities around the United Kingdom.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Other realms signed and read their own proclamations, as did Scotland, Wales, Northern Ireland, the British Overseas Territories, the Crown Dependencies, Canadian provinces and Australian states.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In November 2022, the King and Queen hosted the South African president, Cyril Ramaphosa, during the first official state visit to Britain of Charles's reign.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] The following March, they undertook a state visit to Germany, where Charles became the first British monarch to address the Bundestag.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Nonetheless, the coronation remained a Church of England rite, including the coronation oath, the anointing, crowning, investing with the regalia, and enthronement.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In July 2023, the royal couple attended a national service of thanksgiving at St Giles' Cathedral, where Charles was presented with the Honours of Scotland.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] That same month, he asked for the profits from Britain's growing fleet of offshore wind-farms to be used for the "wider public good" rather than as extra funding for the monarchy, and it was announced that the monarchy's share of Crown Estate net profits would be reduced to 12 per cent.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In September, Charles became the first British monarch to give a speech from the French Senate chamber during a state visit to France.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] The following month he visited Kenya, where he faced calls to apologise for colonial abuses; at a state banquet he acknowledged "abhorrent and unjustifiable acts of violence" but did not issue a formal apology.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In May 2024, the British prime minister, Rishi Sunak, asked the King to call a general election; subsequently, royal engagements that could divert attention from the election campaign were postponed.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In June 2024, Charles and Camilla travelled to Normandy to attend the 80th anniversary commemorations of D-Day.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] The same month, the King received Emperor Naruhito of Japan during his state visit to the United Kingdom.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In July, the annual Holyrood Week, which is usually spent in Scotland, was shortened so that Charles could return to London and appoint a new prime minister following the general election.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] After Sunak's Conservative Party lost the election to the Labour Party led by Sir Keir Starmer, Charles appointed Starmer as prime minister.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In October 2024, the King and Queen toured Australia and Samoa; Australia was the first Commonwealth realm Charles visited since his accession.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In Samoa, he attended the Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting for the first time as Head of the Commonwealth.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] The tour was significantly scaled back owing to his cancer diagnosis, with a planned visit to New Zealand among the cancelled events.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Charles temporarily paused his cancer treatment during the tour.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In March 2025, the King received Ukrainian president Volodymyr Zelenskyy at Sandringham House, just days after the Trump–Zelenskyy Oval Office meeting.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Zelenskyy later told *The Guardian* that Charles played a quiet but influential role in altering US president Donald Trump's attitude toward Ukraine.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] The King and Queen initially cancelled a planned visit to Vatican City during their state visit to Italy, but on 9 April 2025 – their 20th wedding anniversary – they visited Pope Francis at Domus Sanctae Marthae as he was recovering from pneumonia.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] The King, accompanied by the Queen, made his first visit to Canada as monarch in May 2025 at the invitation of Prime Minister Mark Carney, a trip that took place during a period of tension with the United States after President Trump made comments questioning Canada's sovereignty.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] During the visit, he opened the 45th Canadian Parliament and delivered the Speech from the Throne, the first time a Canadian monarch had done so in person since 1977.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In June 2025, the King approved the decommissioning of the British Royal Train ahead of its maintenance contract ending in 2027.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Described by the Keeper of the Privy Purse as part of a commitment to "fiscal discipline", the decision marked the end of 180 years of the royal family's use of a dedicated royal train.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In October 2025, during a state visit to the Holy See, Charles became the first British monarch to pray alongside a pope since the Reformation, joining Pope Leo XIV for a church service in the Sistine Chapel of the Apostolic Palace in Vatican City.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Later that month, Charles undertook his first official engagement in support of the LGBT+ community, unveiling "An Opened Letter", the UK's first national memorial honouring LGBT armed forces veterans, at the National Memorial Arboretum in Staffordshire.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] On 30 October, amid continuing controversy surrounding his brother Andrew's association with the American financier and child sex offender Jeffrey Epstein, Charles initiated a formal process to remove his style, titles and honours.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Following Andrew's arrest on 19 February 2026 on suspicion of misconduct in public office, the King expressed his "deepest concern" and stated that "the law must take its course".
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In April 2026, during a state visit to the United States, Charles became the second British monarch to address a joint meeting of Congress, after his mother Elizabeth II in 1991.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] His speech received around a dozen standing ovations.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In May, he visited Golders Green after the previous month's stabbings, meeting victims at a Jewish Care charity centre, the Chief Rabbi, and members of the community's medical and security response teams.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In June, Buckingham Palace announced that the King would publish his personal tax bills, saying the move was intended to enhance "clarity and accessibility", making him the first head of state to do so.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In March 1998, Charles had laser keyhole surgery on his right knee and in March 2003, he underwent surgery at King Edward VII's Hospital to treat a hernia injury.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In 2008, a non-cancerous growth was removed from his nasal bridge.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In January 2024, Charles underwent a "corrective procedure" at the London Clinic to treat benign prostate enlargement, which resulted in the postponement of some of his public engagements.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In February, Buckingham Palace announced that cancer had been discovered during the treatment, but that it was not prostate cancer.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Although his public duties were postponed, it was reported Charles would continue to fulfil his constitutional functions during his outpatient treatment.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] He released a statement espousing his support for cancer charities and that he "remain[ed] positive" on making a full recovery.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In March, Camilla deputised for him in his absence at the Commonwealth Day service at Westminster Abbey and at the Royal Maundy at Worcester Cathedral.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] He made his first major public appearance since his cancer diagnosis at the Easter service held at St George's Chapel, Windsor Castle, on 31 March.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In April 2024, it was announced that he would resume public-facing duties after making progress in his cancer treatment.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In March 2025, Charles was briefly admitted to hospital after experiencing temporary side effects from his cancer treatment.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] He subsequently postponed several planned engagements.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In December, as part of the Stand Up to Cancer UK campaign hosted by Cancer Research UK and Channel 4, he announced that his treatment schedule would be reduced the following year.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] The King's openness about his illness, contrasting with the traditionally guarded approach of earlier monarchs, was described by the media as unprecedented and as bringing him closer to the public.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] As early as 1985, Charles was questioning meat consumption.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In the *1985 Royal Special* television programme*,* he told the host, Alastair Burnet, that "I actually now don't eat as much meat as I used to.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In 2022, it was reported that he eats a breakfast of fruit salad, seeds, and tea.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] He does not eat lunch, but takes a break for tea at 5:00 pm and eats dinner at 8:30 pm, returning to work until midnight or later.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Ahead of Christmas dinner in 2022, Charles confirmed to the animal rights group People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals that foie gras would not be served at any royal residences; he had stopped the use of foie gras at his own properties for more than a decade before becoming king.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] During a September 2023 state banquet at the Palace of Versailles, it was reported that he did not want foie gras or out-of-season asparagus on the menu.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Since founding the Prince's Trust in 1976, using his £7,500 of severance pay from the Royal Navy, Charles has established 16 more charitable organisations and now serves as president of each.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] King Charles III Charitable Fund has donated over £73 million to various causes since 1979.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] By September 2020 the Prince's Trust had supported over 1,000,000 young people and created 125,000 entrepreneurs.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] As Prince of Wales, Charles became patron or president of more than 800 other charities and organisations.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] He received a Gold Blue Peter badge in 2023 for his environmental work and for his support of young people through the Prince's Trust.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] The Prince's Charities Canada was established in 2010, in a similar fashion to its namesake in Britain.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Charles uses his tours of Canada as a way to help to draw attention to youth, the disabled, the environment, the arts, medicine, the elderly, heritage conservation and education.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] He has also set up the Prince's Charities Australia, based in Melbourne, to provide a co-ordinating presence for his Australian and international charitable endeavours.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Charles has supported humanitarian projects; for example, he has been known to donate his blood to raise awareness for health causes.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Charles and his sons took part in ceremonies that marked the 1998 International Day for the Elimination of Racial Discrimination.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Charles expressed strong concerns about the human rights record of the Romanian dictator Nicolae Ceaușescu.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] After Ceaușescu was deposed, he supported the FARA Foundation, a charity for Romanian orphans and abandoned children.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Charles has also supported humanitarian causes in Israel, including a private donation to the Peres Center for Peace and Innovation in 2020.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] Two of Charles's charities, the Prince's Foundation and the Prince of Wales's Charitable Fund (later renamed the King's Foundation and King Charles III Charitable Fund), came under scrutiny in 2021 and 2022 for accepting donations many in the media deemed inappropriate.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In August 2021 it was announced that the Prince's Foundation was launching an investigation into the reports, with Charles's support.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] The Charity Commission also launched an investigation into allegations that the donations meant for the Prince's Foundation had been instead sent to the Mahfouz Foundation.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In February 2022, the Metropolitan Police launched an investigation into the cash-for-honours allegations linked to the foundation, passing their evidence to the Crown Prosecution Service for deliberation in October.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p01] In August 2023 the Metropolitan Police announced that they had concluded their investigations and no further action would be taken.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] From young adulthood, Charles encouraged the understanding of Indigenous voices, saying they held crucial messages about preservation of the land, respecting community and shared values, resolving conflict, and recognising and making good on past iniquities.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] He dovetailed this view with his efforts against climate change, as well as reconciliation between Indigenous and non-Indigenous peoples and his charitable work in Canada.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] At the 2022 Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting Charles, who was representing his mother, raised that reconciliation process as an example for dealing with the history of slavery in the British Empire, for which he expressed his sorrow.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Letters sent by Charles to British government ministers in 2004 and 2005 expressing his concerns over various policy issues – known as the black spider memos – presented potential embarrassment following a challenge by *The Guardian* to release the letters under the Freedom of Information Act 2000.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] In March 2015 the Supreme Court of the United Kingdom decided that Charles's letters must be released.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] The Cabinet Office published the letters in May that year.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] The reaction was largely supportive of Charles, with little criticism of him; the press variously described the memos as "underwhelming" and "harmless", and concluded that their release had "backfired on those who seek to belittle him".
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] It was revealed in the same year that Charles had access to confidential Cabinet papers.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] In October 2020, a letter sent by Charles to the Governor-General of Australia, Sir John Kerr, after Kerr's dismissal of Prime Minister Gough Whitlam in 1975, was released as part of the collection of palace letters regarding the Australian constitutional crisis.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] In the letter, Charles was supportive of Kerr's decision, writing that what Kerr "did last year was right and the courageous thing to do".
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] In Charles's 1989 book *A Vision of Britain*, and in speeches and essays, he has been critical of modern architecture, arguing that traditional designs and methods should guide contemporary ones.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] He has continued to campaign for traditional urbanism, human scale, restoration of historic buildings, and sustainable design despite criticism in the press.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Two of his charities – the Prince's Regeneration Trust and the Prince's Foundation for Building Community, which were later merged into one charity – promote his views.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] The village of Poundbury was built on land owned by the Duchy of Cornwall to a master plan by Léon Krier, under the guidance of Charles and in line with his philosophy.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] In 2013 developments for the suburb of Nansledan began on the estate of the Duchy of Cornwall with Charles's endorsement.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Charles helped purchase Dumfries House and its complete collection of 18th century furnishings in 2007, taking a £20 million loan from his charitable trust to contribute towards the £45 million cost.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] The house and gardens remain property of the Prince's Foundation and serve as a museum and community and skills training centre.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] This led to the development of Knockroon, called the "Scottish Poundbury".
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] In 2025, it was reported that the design of a new generation of British towns would incorporate Charles's architectural ideas.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] After lamenting in 1996 the unbridled destruction of many of Canada's historic urban cores, Charles offered his assistance to the Department of Canadian Heritage in creating a trust modelled on Britain's National Trust, a plan that was implemented with the passage of the federal budget in 2007.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] In 1999 Charles agreed to the use of his title for the Prince of Wales Prize for Municipal Heritage Leadership, awarded by the National Trust for Canada to municipal governments that have committed to the conservation of historic places.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Whilst visiting the US and surveying the damage caused by Hurricane Katrina, Charles received the National Building Museum's Vincent Scully Prize in 2005 for his efforts in regard to architecture; he donated US$25,000 of the prize money towards restoring storm-damaged communities.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] For his work as patron of New Classical architecture, Charles was awarded the 2012 Driehaus Architecture Prize from the University of Notre Dame.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Charles has occasionally intervened in projects that employ architectural styles such as modernism and functionalism.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] In 2009 he wrote to the Qatari royal family – the financier of the redevelopment of the Chelsea Barracks site – labelling Lord Rogers's design for the site "unsuitable".
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Rogers claimed that Charles had also intervened to block his designs for the Royal Opera House and Paternoster Square.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] CPC Group, the project developer, took a case against Qatari Diar to the High Court.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] After the suit was settled, the CPC Group apologised to Charles "for any offence caused ... during the course of the proceedings".
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Since the 1970s, Charles has promoted environmental awareness.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] At the age of 21 he delivered his first speech on environmental issues in his capacity as the chairman of the Welsh Countryside Committee.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Charles was named one of Time Magazine's 100 most influential climate leaders of 2025.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] An avid gardener, Charles has also emphasised the importance of talking to plants, stating that "I happily talk to the plants and trees, and listen to them.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] His interest in gardening began in 1980 when he took over the Highgrove estate.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] His "healing garden", based on sacred geometry and ancient religious symbolism, went on display at the Chelsea Flower Show in 2002.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Charles became involved with farming and various industries within it, regularly meeting with farmers to discuss their trade.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] A prominent critic of the practice, Charles has also spoken against the use of genetically modified crops, and in a letter to Tony Blair in 1998 he criticised the development of genetically modified foods.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] The Sustainable Markets Initiative – a project that encourages putting sustainability at the centre of all activities – was launched by Charles at the World Economic Forum's annual meeting in Davos in January 2020.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] In May of the same year, the initiative and the World Economic Forum initiated the Great Reset project, a five-point plan concerned with enhancing sustainable economic growth following the global recession caused by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] The holy chrism oil used at Charles's coronation was vegan, made from oils of olive, sesame, rose, jasmine, cinnamon, neroli and benzoin, along with amber and orange blossom.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] His mother's chrism oil contained animal-based oils.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Charles delivered a speech at the 2021 G20 Rome summit, describing COP26 as "the last chance saloon" for preventing climate change and asking for actions that would lead to a green-led, sustainable economy.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] In his speech at the opening ceremony for COP26, he repeated his sentiments from the previous year, stating that "a vast military-style campaign" was needed "to marshal the strength of the global private sector" for tackling climate change.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] In 2022, the media alleged that Liz Truss had advised Charles against attending COP27, to which advice he agreed.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] In 2010, he funded the Prince's Countryside Fund (renamed the Royal Countryside Fund in 2023), a charity that aims for a "confident, robust and sustainable agricultural and rural community".
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Charles has controversially championed alternative medicine, including homeopathy.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] He first publicly expressed his interest in the topic in December 1982, in an address to the British Medical Association.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] This speech was seen as "combative" and "critical" of modern medicine and was met with anger by some medical professionals.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Similarly, the Prince's Foundation for Integrated Health (FIH) attracted opposition from the scientific and medical community over its campaign encouraging general practitioners to offer herbal and other alternative treatments to NHS patients.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] In April 2008, *The Times* published a letter from Edzard Ernst, professor of complementary medicine at the University of Exeter, which asked the FIH to recall two guides promoting alternative medicine.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] That year, Ernst published a book with Simon Singh called *Trick or Treatment: Alternative Medicine on Trial* and mockingly dedicated to "HRH the Prince of Wales".
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] The last chapter is highly critical of Charles's advocacy of complementary and alternative treatments.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Charles's Duchy Originals produced a variety of complementary medicinal products, including a "Detox Tincture" that Ernst denounced as "financially exploiting the vulnerable" and "outright quackery".
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Charles personally wrote at least seven letters to the Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency shortly before it relaxed the rules governing labelling of such herbal products, a move that was widely condemned by scientists and medical bodies.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] It was reported in October 2009 that Charles had lobbied the health secretary, Andy Burnham, regarding greater provision of alternative treatments in the NHS.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Following accounting irregularities, the FIH announced its closure in April 2010.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] The FIH was re-branded and re-launched later in 2010 as the College of Medicine, of which Charles became a patron in 2019.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] From his youth until 2005, Charles was an avid player of competitive polo.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Charles also frequently took part in fox hunting until the sport was banned in the United Kingdom, also in 2005.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] By the late 1990s opposition to the activity was growing when Charles's participation was viewed as a "political statement" by those who were opposed to it.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Charles suffered several polo- and hunting-related injuries throughout the years, including a two-inch scar on his left cheek in 1980, a broken arm in 1990, a torn cartilage in his left knee in 1992, a broken rib in 1998, and a fractured shoulder in 2001.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Charles has been a keen salmon angler since youth and supported Orri Vigfússon's efforts to protect the North Atlantic salmon.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] He frequently fishes the River Dee in Aberdeenshire, and claims his most special angling memories are from his time spent in Vopnafjörður, Iceland.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Apart from hunting, Charles has also participated in target rifle competitions, representing the House of Lords in the Vizianagram Match (Lords vs.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] He became President of the British National Rifle Association in 1977.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Charles has been involved in performance since his youth, and appeared in sketches and revues while studying at Cambridge.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] In 2000 he revived the tradition of appointing an official harpist to the Prince of Wales, in order to foster Welsh talent at playing the national instrument of Wales.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] The role, now referred to as King's Harpist, is currently held by Mared Pugh Evans.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Charles is a keen watercolourist, having published books on the subject and exhibited and sold a number of his works to raise money for charity; in 2016 it was estimated that he had sold lithographs of his watercolours for a total of £2 million from a shop at his Highgrove House residence.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] For his 50th birthday 50 of his watercolours were exhibited at Hampton Court Palace and, for his 70th birthday, his works were exhibited at the National Gallery of Australia.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Charles founded the Royal Drawing School in 2000, which offers drawing classes to children and the public.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] In 2001, 20 lithographs of his watercolour paintings illustrating his country estates were exhibited at the Florence International Biennale of Contemporary Art and 79 of his paintings were put on display in London in 2022.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] To mark the 25th anniversary of his investiture as Prince of Wales in 1994, the Royal Mail issued a series of postage stamps that featured his paintings.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Charles is the author of several books and has contributed a foreword or preface to numerous books by others.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] He has also been featured in a variety of documentary films.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Shortly after his accession to the throne, Charles publicly described himself as "a committed Anglican Christian"; at age 16, during Easter 1965, he had been confirmed into the Anglican Communion by Archbishop of Canterbury Michael Ramsey in St George's Chapel, Windsor Castle.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] The King is the Supreme Governor of the Church of England and a member of the Church of Scotland; he swore an oath to uphold that church immediately after he was proclaimed King.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] He attends services at various Anglican churches close to Highgrove and attends the Church of Scotland's Crathie Kirk with the rest of the royal family when staying at Balmoral Castle.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Laurens van der Post became a friend of Charles in 1977; he was dubbed Charles's "spiritual guru" and was godfather to Prince William.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] From van der Post, Charles developed a focus on philosophy and an interest in other religions.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Charles expressed his philosophical views in his 2010 book, *Harmony: A New Way of Looking at Our World*, which won a Nautilus Book Award.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Charles also attended the consecration of Britain's first Syriac Orthodox cathedral, St Thomas Cathedral, Acton.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Charles is patron of the Oxford Centre for Islamic Studies at the University of Oxford and attended the inauguration of the Markfield Institute of Higher Education, which is dedicated to Islamic studies in a multicultural context.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] He stated in 2015 that he would retain the title of *Defender of the Faith*, whilst "ensuring that other people's faiths can also be practised", which he sees as a duty of the Church of England.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] His inclusive, multi-faith approach and his own Christian beliefs were expressed in his first Christmas message as king.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] In line with his multi-faith approach, Charles has served as a patron of the Council of Christians and Jews and of the Jewish Museum London.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Since his birth, Charles has received close media attention, which increased as he matured.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] It has been an ambivalent relationship, largely impacted by his marriages to Diana and Camilla and their aftermath, but also centred on his future conduct as king.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Described as the "world's most eligible bachelor" in the late 1970s, Charles was subsequently overshadowed by Diana.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] After her death the media regularly breached Charles's privacy and printed exposés.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Known for expressing his opinions, when asked during an interview to mark his 70th birthday whether this would continue in the same way once he is King, he responded "No.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] I do realise that it is a separate exercise being sovereign.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] So, of course, you know, I understand entirely how that should operate." In September 2025, *The Economist* analysed all Charles's public speeches over the past 30 years and concluded that he has mellowed over the past three decades.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] In 2009, Charles was named the world's best-dressed man by *Esquire* magazine.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Fashion magazine *British GQ* described Charles as "the true guardian of traditional British menswear" in 2012 and named him one of the most stylish people of 2025.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Italian designer Donatella Versace once said Charles "is an archetype of style".
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] In 2023 the *New Statesman* named Charles as the fourth-most-powerful right-wing figure of the year, describing him as a "romantic traditionalist" and "the very last reactionary in public life" for his support of various traditionalist think tanks and previous writings.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] He was also named one of the 100 most influential people of 2023 by *Time* magazine.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Charles and Camilla topped *Tatler*'s Social Power Index for 2022 and 2023.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] A 2018 BMG Research poll found that 46 per cent of Britons wanted Charles to abdicate immediately on his mother's death, in favour of William.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] However, a 2021 opinion poll reported that 60 percent of the British public had a favourable opinion of him.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] On his accession to the throne, *The Statesman* reported an opinion poll that put Charles's popularity with the British people at 42 per cent.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] More recent polling suggested that his popularity increased sharply after he became King.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] As of August 2025, Charles continues to hold majority support with an approval rating of 59 per cent, and 62 percent of the public say "he is doing a good job", according to YouGov.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] In 1994, the German tabloid *Bild* published nude photos of Charles that were taken while he was vacationing in Le Barroux; they had reportedly been put up for sale for £30,000.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Buckingham Palace reacted by stating that it was "unjustifiable for anybody to suffer this sort of intrusion".
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Charles, "so often a target of the press, got his chance to return fire" in 2002, when addressing "scores of editors, publishers, and other media executives" gathered at St Bride's Fleet Street to celebrate 300 years of journalism.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Charles and Camilla were named in 2011 as individuals whose confidential information was reportedly targeted or actually acquired in conjunction with the news media phone hacking scandal.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] In 2023, *The Guardian* estimated Charles's personal wealth at £1.8 billion.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Most of this wealth, which he inherited from his mother, Elizabeth II, was exempt from inheritance tax.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Clarence House, previously the residence of the Queen Mother, has been Charles's official London residence from 2003, after being renovated at a cost of £6.1 million.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] He previously shared apartments eight and nine at Kensington Palace with Diana before moving to York House at St James's Palace, which remained his principal residence until 2003.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Highgrove House in Gloucestershire is owned by the Duchy of Cornwall, having been purchased for Charles's use in 1980, and which he rented for £336,000 per annum.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Since William became Duke of Cornwall, Charles is expected to pay £700,000 per annum for use of the property.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Charles also owns a property near the village of Viscri in Romania.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] As Prince of Wales, Charles's primary source of income was generated from the Duchy of Cornwall, which owns 133,658 acres of land (around 54,090 hectares), including farming, residential, and commercial properties, as well as an investment portfolio.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Since 1993, he has paid tax voluntarily under the *Memorandum of Understanding on Royal Taxation*, updated in 2013.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Her Majesty's Revenue and Customs were asked in December 2012 to investigate alleged tax avoidance by the Duchy of Cornwall.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] The Duchy was named in the Paradise Papers, a set of confidential electronic documents relating to offshore investment that were leaked to the German newspaper *Süddeutsche Zeitung* in 2017.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] In the 2021–22 financial year, Charles received £23 million from the Duchy of Cornwall and paid a voluntary income tax of £5.9 million.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] In June 2026, Charles revealed that he had paid £12.9 million in tax for the 2024–25 financial year, and it was also announced that, once the renovations at Buckingham Palace are completed, he and Camilla will not be moving into the palace.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Charles has held many titles and honorary military positions throughout the Commonwealth, is sovereign of many orders in his own countries and has received honours and awards from around the world.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] In each of his realms he has a distinct title that follows a similar formula: *King of Saint Lucia and of His other Realms and Territories* in Saint Lucia, *King of Australia and His other Realms and Territories* in Australia, etc.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] In the Isle of Man, which is a Crown Dependency rather than a separate realm, he is known as Lord of Mann.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Charles is also styled *Defender of the Faith*.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] There had been speculation throughout Elizabeth II's reign as to what regnal name Charles would choose upon his accession; instead of *Charles III*, he could have chosen to reign as *George VII* or used one of his other given names.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] It was reported that he might use George in honour of his grandfather George VI and to avoid associations with previous controversial kings named Charles.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Charles's office asserted in 2005 that no decision had yet been made.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Speculation continued for a few hours following his mother's death, until Prime Minister Liz Truss announced and Clarence House confirmed that Charles had chosen the regnal name *Charles III*.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] Charles, who left active military service in 1976, was awarded the highest rank in all three armed services in 2012 by his mother: Admiral of the Fleet, Field Marshal, and Marshal of the Royal Air Force.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] When Charles became king, he inherited the royal coats of arms of the United Kingdom and of Canada.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] The design of his royal cypher, featuring a depiction of the Tudor Crown instead of St Edward's Crown, was revealed on 27 September 2022.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] The College of Arms envisaged that the Tudor crown will be used in new arms, uniforms and crown badges as they are replaced.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] On 10 October 2024, designed by artist Timothy Noad, the new Royal Arms, alongside the new Lesser Arms, used by the UK government were officially unveiled, with both arms reflecting the stylistic changes made after Charles's accession.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] The banners used by Charles as Prince of Wales varied depending upon location.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] His personal standard for the United Kingdom was the Royal Standard of the United Kingdom differenced as in his arms, with a label of three points *argent* and the escutcheon of the arms of the Principality of Wales in the centre.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] It was used outside Wales, Scotland, Cornwall and Canada, and throughout the entire United Kingdom when Charles was acting in an official capacity associated with the British Armed Forces.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] The personal flag for use in Wales was based upon the Royal Badge of Wales.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] In Scotland the personal banner used between 1974 and 2022 was based upon three ancient Scottish titles: Duke of Rothesay (heir apparent to the King of Scots), High Steward of Scotland, and Lord of the Isles.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] In Cornwall, the banner was the arms of the Duke of Cornwall.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] The royal standard of the United Kingdom is used to represent the King in the United Kingdom and on official visits overseas, except in Australia and Canada.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] It is the royal arms in banner form undifferentiated, having been used by successive British monarchs since 1702.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] The royal standard of Canada is used by the King in Canada and while acting on behalf of Canada overseas.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] It is the *escutcheon* of the Royal Coat of Arms of Canada in banner form undifferentiated.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/charles-iii-p02] As Prince of Wales, Charles wrote four books and was a co-author of other works.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/colchicum-autumnale] The species is cultivated as an ornamental in temperate areas, in spite of its toxicity.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/colchicum-autumnale] The cultivar 'Nancy Lindsay' has gained the Royal Horticultural Society's Award of Garden Merit.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/colchicum-autumnale] This herbaceous perennial has leaves up to 25 cm (10 in) long.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/colchicum-autumnale] The flowers are solitary, 4–7 cm (2–3 in) across, with six tepals and six stamens with orange anthers and three white styles.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/colchicum-autumnale] At the time of fertilisation, the ovary is below ground.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/colchicum-autumnale] The bulb-like corms of *C. autumnale* contain colchicine, a useful drug with a narrow therapeutic index.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/colchicum-autumnale] Colchicine is approved in many countries for the treatment of gout and familial Mediterranean fever.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/colchicum-autumnale] Colchicine is also used in plant breeding to produce polyploid strains.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/colchicum-autumnale] This plant (and colchicine itself) poses a particular threat to felines.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/colchicum-autumnale] The corms of meadow saffron contain the highest level of toxins, but all parts of the plant are regarded as poisonous.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] The conservation ethic is based on the findings of conservation biology.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] The term conservation biology and its conception as a new field originated with the convening of "The First International Conference on Research in Conservation Biology" held at the University of California, San Diego in La Jolla, California, in 1978 led by American biologists Bruce A.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Soulé with a group of leading university and zoo researchers and conservationists including Kurt Benirschke, Sir Otto Frankel, Thomas Lovejoy, and Jared Diamond.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] The meeting was prompted due to concern over tropical deforestation, disappearing species, and eroding genetic diversity within species.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] The conference and proceedings that resulted sought to initiate the bridging of a gap between theory in ecology and evolutionary genetics on the one hand and conservation policy and practice on the other.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Conservation biology and the concept of biological diversity (biodiversity) emerged together, helping crystallize the modern era of conservation science and policy.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] The inherent multidisciplinary basis for conservation biology has led to new subdisciplines including conservation social science, conservation behavior and conservation physiology.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] It stimulated further development of conservation genetics which Otto Frankel had originated first but is now often considered a subdiscipline as well.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] The rapid decline of established biological systems around the world means that conservation biology is often referred to as a "Discipline with a deadline".
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Conservation biology is tied closely to ecology in researching the population ecology (dispersal, migration, demographics, effective population size, inbreeding depression, and minimum population viability) of rare or endangered species.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Conservation biology is concerned with phenomena that affect the maintenance, loss, and restoration of biodiversity and the science of sustaining evolutionary processes that engender genetic, population, species, and ecosystem diversity.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] The concern stems from estimates suggesting that up to 50% of all species on the planet will disappear within the next 50 years, which will increase poverty and starvation, and will reset the course of evolution on this planet.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Researchers acknowledge that projections are difficult, given the unknown potential impacts of many variables, including species introduction to new biogeographical settings and a non-analog climate.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Conservation biologists research and educate on the trends and process of biodiversity loss, species extinctions, and the negative effect these are having on our capabilities to sustain the well-being of human society.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Conservation biologists work in the field and office, in government, universities, non-profit organizations and industry.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] The topics of their research are diverse, because this is an interdisciplinary network with professional alliances in the biological as well as social sciences.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Those dedicated to the cause and profession advocate for a global response to the current biodiversity crisis based on morals, ethics, and scientific reason.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Organizations and citizens are responding to the biodiversity crisis through conservation action plans that direct research, monitoring, and education programs that engage concerns at local through global scales.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] There is increasing recognition that conservation is not just about what is achieved but how it is done.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Conscious efforts to conserve and protect *global* biodiversity are a recent phenomenon.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Natural resource conservation, however, has a history that extends prior to the age of conservation.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Resource ethics grew out of necessity through direct relations with nature.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Regulation or communal restraint became necessary to prevent selfish motives from taking more than could be locally sustained, therefore compromising the long-term supply for the rest of the community.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] This social dilemma with respect to natural resource management is often called the "tragedy of the commons".
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] From this principle, conservation biologists can trace communal resource based ethics throughout cultures as a solution to communal resource conflict.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] For example, the Alaskan Tlingit peoples and the Haida of the Pacific Northwest had resource boundaries, rules, and restrictions among clans with respect to the fishing of sockeye salmon.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] These rules were guided by clan elders who knew lifelong details of each river and stream they managed.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] There are numerous examples in history where cultures have followed rules, rituals, and organized practice with respect to communal natural resource management.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] The Mauryan emperor Ashoka around 250 BC issued edicts restricting the slaughter of animals and certain kinds of birds, as well as opened veterinary clinics.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Conservation ethics are also found in early religious and philosophical writings.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] There are examples in the Tao, Shinto, Hindu, Islamic and Buddhist traditions.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Before the 18th century, however, much of European culture considered it a pagan view to admire nature.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Wilderness was denigrated while agricultural development was praised.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] However, as early as AD 680 a wildlife sanctuary was founded on the Farne Islands by St Cuthbert in response to his religious beliefs.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Natural history was a major preoccupation in the 18th century, with grand expeditions and the opening of popular public displays in Europe and North America.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] By 1900 there were 150 natural history museums in Germany, 250 in Great Britain, 250 in the United States, and 300 in France.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Preservationist or conservationist sentiments are a development of the late 18th to early 20th centuries.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Before Charles Darwin set sail on HMS *Beagle*, most people in the world, including Darwin, believed in special creation and that all species were unchanged.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Georges-Louis Leclerc, Comte de Buffon was one of the first naturalists that questioned this belief.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] He proposed in his 44 volume natural history book that species evolve due to environmental influences.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Erasmus Darwin was also a naturalist who also suggested that species evolved.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Erasmus Darwin noted that some species have vestigial structures which are anatomical structures that have no apparent function in the species currently but would have been useful for the species' ancestors.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] The thinking of these early 18th century naturalists helped to change the mindset and thinking of the early 19th century naturalists.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] By the early 19th century biogeography was ignited through the efforts of Alexander von Humboldt, Charles Lyell and Charles Darwin.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] The 19th-century fascination with natural history engendered a fervor to be the first to collect rare specimens with the goal of doing so before they became extinct by other such collectors.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Although the work of many 18th and 19th century naturalists were to inspire nature enthusiasts and conservation organizations, their writings, by modern standards, showed insensitivity towards conservation as they would kill hundreds of specimens for their collections.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] The modern roots of conservation biology can be found in the late 18th-century Enlightenment period particularly in England and Scotland.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Thinkers including Lord Monboddo described the importance of "preserving nature"; much of this early emphasis had its origins in Christian theology.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Scientific conservation principles were first practically applied to the forests of British India.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] The Madras Board of Revenue started local conservation efforts in 1842, headed by Alexander Gibson, a professional botanist who systematically adopted a forest conservation program based on scientific principles.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] This was the first case of state conservation management of forests in the world.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Governor-General Lord Dalhousie introduced the first permanent and large-scale forest conservation program in the world in 1855, a model that soon spread to other colonies, as well the United States, where Yellowstone National Park was opened in 1872 as the world's first national park.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] The term *conservation* came into widespread use in the late 19th century and referred to the management, mainly for economic reasons, of such natural resources as timber, fish, game, topsoil, pastureland, and minerals.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] In addition it referred to the preservation of forests (forestry), wildlife (wildlife refuge), parkland, wilderness, and watersheds.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] This period also saw the passage of the first conservation legislation and the establishment of the first nature conservation societies.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] The Sea Birds Preservation Act 1869 was passed in Britain as the first nature protection law in the world after extensive lobbying from the Association for the Protection of Seabirds and the respected ornithologist Alfred Newton.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Newton was also instrumental in the passage of the first Game laws from 1872, which protected animals during their breeding season so as to prevent the stock from being brought close to extinction.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] One of the first conservation societies was the Royal Society for the Protection of Birds, founded in 1889 in Manchester as a protest group campaigning against the use of great crested grebe and kittiwake skins and feathers in fur clothing.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Originally known as "the Plumage League", the group gained popularity and eventually amalgamated with the Fur and Feather League in Croydon, and formed the RSPB.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] This meeting led to the formation of the Society for the Promotion of Nature Reserves, which later became the Wildlife Trusts.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] In the United States, the Forest Reserve Act of 1891 gave the President power to set aside forest reserves from the land in the public domain.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] John Muir founded the Sierra Club in 1892, and the New York Zoological Society was set up in 1895.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] A series of national forests and preserves were established by Theodore Roosevelt from 1901 to 1909.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] The 1916 National Parks Act, included a 'use without impairment' clause, sought by John Muir, which eventually resulted in the removal of a proposal to build a dam in Dinosaur National Monument in 1959.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] In the 20th century, Canadian civil servants, including Charles Gordon Hewitt and James Harkin, spearheaded the movement toward wildlife conservation.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] In the 21st century professional conservation officers have begun to collaborate with indigenous communities for protecting wildlife in Canada.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Some conservation efforts are yet to fully take hold due to ecological neglect.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] For example in the USA, 21st century bowfishing of native fishes, which amounts to killing wild animals for recreation and disposing of them immediately afterwards, remains unregulated and unmanaged.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] In the mid-20th century, efforts arose to target individual species for conservation, notably efforts in big cat conservation in South America led by the New York Zoological Society.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Akeley, Archie Carr and his son Archie Carr III is notable in this era.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Akeley for example, having led expeditions to the Virunga Mountains and observed the mountain gorilla in the wild, became convinced that the species and the area were conservation priorities.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] He was instrumental in persuading Albert I of Belgium to act in defense of the mountain gorilla and establish Albert National Park (since renamed Virunga National Park) in what is now Democratic Republic of Congo.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] By the 1970s, led primarily by work in the United States under the Endangered Species Act along with the Species at Risk Act (SARA) of Canada, Biodiversity Action Plans developed in Australia, Sweden, the United Kingdom, hundreds of species specific protection plans ensued.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Notably the United Nations acted to conserve sites of outstanding cultural or natural importance to the common heritage of mankind.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] The programme was adopted by the General Conference of UNESCO in 1972.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] As of 2006, a total of 830 sites are listed: 644 cultural, 162 natural.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Other conservation developments, however, have taken hold throughout the world.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] India, for example, passed the Wildlife Protection Act, 1972.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] In 1980, a significant development was the emergence of the urban conservation movement.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] A local organization was established in Birmingham, UK, a development followed in rapid succession in cities across the UK, then overseas.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Although perceived as a grassroots movement, its early development was driven by academic research into urban wildlife.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Initially perceived as radical, the movement's view of conservation being inextricably linked with other human activity has now become mainstream in conservation thought.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Considerable research effort is now directed at urban conservation biology.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] The Society for Conservation Biology originated in 1985.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] The late 1990s saw increasing professionalism in the sector, with the maturing of organisations such as the Institute of Ecology and Environmental Management and the Society for the Environment.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Since 2000, the concept of landscape scale conservation has risen to prominence, with less emphasis being given to single-species or even single-habitat focused actions.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Instead an ecosystem approach is advocated by most mainstream conservationists, although concerns have been expressed by those working to protect some high-profile species.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Ecology has clarified the workings of the biosphere; i.e., the complex interrelationships among humans, other species, and the physical environment.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] The burgeoning human population and associated agriculture, industry, and the ensuing pollution, have demonstrated how easily ecological relationships can be disrupted.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] becoming extinct during any given time interval.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] It does not represent all marine species, just those that are readily fossilized.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Extinction rates are measured in a variety of ways.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Conservation biologists measure and apply statistical measures of fossil records, rates of habitat loss, and a multitude of other variables such as loss of biodiversity as a function of the rate of habitat loss and site occupancy to obtain such estimates.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] *The Theory of Island Biogeography* is possibly the most significant contribution toward the scientific understanding of both the process and how to measure the rate of species extinction.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] The current background extinction rate is estimated to be one species every few years.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Actual extinction rates are estimated to be orders of magnitudes higher.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] While this is important, it's worth noting that there are no models in existence that account for the complexity of unpredictable factors like species movement, a non-analog climate, changing species interactions, evolutionary rates on finer time scales, and many other stochastic variables.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] The measure of ongoing species loss is made more complex by the fact that most of the Earth's species have not been described or evaluated.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Estimates vary greatly on how many species actually exist (estimated range: 3,600,000–111,700,000) to how many have received a species binomial (estimated range: 1.5–8 million).
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Less than 1 percent of all species that have been described beyond simply noting its existence.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] From these figures, the IUCN reports that 23 percent of vertebrates, 5 percent of invertebrates and 70 percent of plants that have been evaluated are designated as endangered or threatened.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Better knowledge is being constructed by The Plant List for actual numbers of species.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Systematic conservation planning is an effective way to seek and identify efficient and effective types of reserve design to capture or sustain the highest priority biodiversity values and to work with communities in support of local ecosystems.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Conservation biologists regularly prepare detailed conservation plans for grant proposals or to effectively coordinate their plan of action and to identify best management practices (e.g.).
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Systematic strategies generally employ the services of Geographic Information Systems to assist in the decision-making process.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] The SLOSS debate is often considered in planning.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Conservation physiology was defined by Steven J.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Conservation physiology is particularly relevant to practitioners in that it has the potential to generate cause-and-effect relationships and reveal the factors that contribute to population declines.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] The Society for Conservation Biology is a global community of conservation professionals dedicated to advancing the science and practice of conserving biodiversity.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Conservation biology as a discipline reaches beyond biology, into subjects such as philosophy, law, economics, humanities, arts, anthropology, and education.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Within biology, conservation genetics and evolution are immense fields unto themselves, but these disciplines are of prime importance to the practice and profession of conservation biology.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Conservationists introduce bias when they support policies using qualitative description, such as habitat *degradation*, or *healthy* ecosystems.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Conservation biologists advocate for reasoned and sensible management of natural resources and do so with a disclosed combination of science, reason, logic, and values in their conservation management plans.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] This sort of advocacy is similar to the medical profession advocating for healthy lifestyle options, both are beneficial to human well-being yet remain scientific in their approach.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] There is a movement in conservation biology suggesting a new form of leadership is needed to mobilize conservation biology into a more effective discipline that is able to communicate the full scope of the problem to society at large.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] The movement proposes an adaptive leadership approach that parallels an adaptive management approach.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] The concept is based on a new philosophy or leadership theory steering away from historical notions of power, authority, and dominance.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Adaptive conservation leadership is reflective and more equitable as it applies to any member of society who can mobilize others toward meaningful change using communication techniques that are inspiring, purposeful, and collegial.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Adaptive conservation leadership and mentoring programs are being implemented by conservation biologists through organizations such as the Aldo Leopold Leadership Program.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Conservation may be classified as either in-situ conservation, which is protecting an endangered species in its natural habitat, or ex-situ conservation, which occurs outside the natural habitat.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] In-situ conservation involves protecting or restoring the habitat.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Ex-situ conservation, on the other hand, involves protection outside of an organism's natural habitat, such as on reservations or in gene banks, in circumstances where viable populations may not be present in the natural habitat.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] The conservation of habitats like forest, water or soil in its natural state is crucial for any species depending in it to thrive.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Making a new environment which looks alike the original is less effective than preserving original habitats.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] An approach in Nepal named reforestation campaign has helped increase the density and area covered by the original forests which proved to be better than creating entirely new environment after original one is let to lost.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Old Forests Store More Carbon than Young Ones as proved by latest researches, so it is more crucial to protect the old ones.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] The reforestation campaign launched by Himalayan Adventure Therapy in Nepal basically visits the old forests in periodic basis which are vulnerable to loss of density and the area covered due to unplanned urbanization activities.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Then they plant the new saplings of same tree families of that existing forest in the areas where the old forest has been lost and also plant those saplings to the barren areas connected to the forest.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] This maintains the density and area covered by the forest.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Also, non-interference may be used, which is termed a preservationist method.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Preservationists advocate for giving areas of nature and species a protected existence that halts interference from the humans.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] In this regard, conservationists differ from preservationists in the social dimension, as conservation biology engages society and seeks equitable solutions for both society and ecosystems.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Some preservationists emphasize the potential of biodiversity in a world without humans.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Ecological monitoring is the systematic collection of data relevant to the ecology of a species or habitat at repeating intervals with defined methods.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Long-term monitoring for environmental and ecological metrics is an important part of any successful conservation initiative.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Unfortunately, long-term data for many species and habitats is not available in many cases.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] A lack of historical data on species populations, habitats, and ecosystems means that any current or future conservation work will have to make assumptions to determine if the work is having any effect on the population or ecosystem health.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Ecological monitoring can provide early warning signals of deleterious effects (from human activities or natural changes in an environment) on an ecosystem and its species.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] In order for signs of negative trends in ecosystem or species health to be detected, monitoring methods must be carried out at appropriate time intervals, and the metric must be able to capture the trend of the population or habitat as a whole.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Long-term monitoring can include the continued measuring of many biological, ecological, and environmental metrics including annual breeding success, population size estimates, water quality, biodiversity (which can be measured in many way, i.e.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] When determining which metrics to monitor for a conservation project, it is important to understand how an ecosystem functions and what role different species and abiotic factors have within the system.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Another benefit of ecological monitoring is the hard evidence it provides scientists to use for advising policy makers and funding bodies about conservation efforts.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Not only is ecological monitoring data important for convincing politicians, funders, and the public why a conservation program is important to implement, but also to keep them convinced that a program should be continued to be supported.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] There is plenty of debate on how conservation resources can be used most efficiently; even within ecological monitoring, there is debate on which metrics that money, time and personnel should be dedicated to for the best chance of making a positive impact.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] The concept of bioindicators / indicator species can be applied to ecological monitoring as a way to investigate how pollution is affecting an ecosystem.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Species like amphibians and birds are highly susceptible to pollutants in their environment due to their behaviours and physiological features that cause them to absorb pollutants at a faster rate than other species.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Amphibians spend parts of their time in the water and on land, making them susceptible to changes in both environments.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] They also have very permeable skin that allows them to breathe and intake water, which means they also take any air or water-soluble pollutants in as well.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Birds often cover a wide range in habitat types annually, and also generally revisit the same nesting site each year.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] This makes it easier for researchers to track ecological effects at both an individual and a population level for the species.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Many conservation researchers believe that having a long-term ecological monitoring program should be a priority for conservation projects, protected areas, and regions where environmental harm mitigation is used.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Conservation biologists are interdisciplinary researchers that practice ethics in the biological and social sciences.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Chan states that conservationists must advocate for biodiversity and can do so in a scientifically ethical manner by not promoting simultaneous advocacy against other competing values.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Aldo Leopold was a classical thinker and writer on such conservation ethics whose philosophy, ethics and writings are still valued and revisited by modern conservation biologists.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] The International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN) has organized a global assortment of scientists and research stations across the planet to monitor the changing state of nature in an effort to tackle the extinction crisis.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] The IUCN provides annual updates on the status of species conservation through its Red List.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] The IUCN Red List serves as an international conservation tool to identify those species most in need of conservation attention and by providing a global index on the status of biodiversity.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] More than the dramatic rates of species loss, however, conservation scientists note that the sixth mass extinction is a biodiversity crisis requiring far more action than a priority focus on rare, endemic or endangered species.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Concerns for biodiversity loss covers a broader conservation mandate that looks at ecological processes, such as migration, and a holistic examination of biodiversity at levels beyond the species, including genetic, population and ecosystem diversity.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Extensive, systematic, and rapid rates of biodiversity loss threatens the sustained well-being of humanity by limiting supply of ecosystem services that are otherwise regenerated by the complex and evolving holistic network of genetic and ecosystem diversity.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] While the conservation status of species is employed extensively in conservation management, some scientists highlight that it is the common species that are the primary source of exploitation and habitat alteration by humanity.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Moreover, common species are often undervalued despite their role as the primary source of ecosystem services.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] While most in the community of conservation science "stress the importance" of sustaining biodiversity, there is debate on how to prioritize genes, species, or ecosystems, which are all components of biodiversity (e.g.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] The costs of discovering, naming, and mapping out the distribution of every species, they argue, is an ill-advised conservation venture.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] They reason it is better to understand the significance of the ecological roles of species.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Biodiversity hotspots and coldspots are a way of recognizing that the spatial concentration of genes, species, and ecosystems is not uniformly distributed on the Earth's surface.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Those arguing in favor of setting priorities for coldspots point out that there are other measures to consider beyond biodiversity.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] They point out that emphasizing hotspots downplays the importance of the social and ecological connections to vast areas of the Earth's ecosystems where biomass, not biodiversity, reigns supreme.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] It is estimated that 36 percent of the Earth's surface, encompassing 38.9 percent of the worlds vertebrates, lacks the endemic species to qualify as biodiversity hotspot.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Moreover, measures show that maximizing protections for biodiversity does not capture ecosystem services any better than targeting randomly chosen regions.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Population level biodiversity (mostly in coldspots) are disappearing at a rate that is ten times that at the species level.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] The level of importance in addressing biomass versus endemism as a concern for conservation biology is highlighted in literature measuring the level of threat to global ecosystem carbon stocks that do not necessarily reside in areas of endemism.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] A hotspot priority approach would not invest so heavily in places such as steppes, the Serengeti, the Arctic, or taiga.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] These areas contribute a great abundance of population (not species) level biodiversity and ecosystem services, including cultural value and planetary nutrient cycling.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Those in favor of the hotspot approach point out that species are irreplaceable components of the global ecosystem, they are concentrated in places that are most threatened, and should therefore receive maximal strategic protections.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] This is a hotspot approach because the priority is set to target species level concerns over population level or biomass.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Species richness and genetic biodiversity contributes to and engenders ecosystem stability, ecosystem processes, evolutionary adaptability, and biomass.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Both sides agree, however, that conserving biodiversity is necessary to reduce the extinction rate and identify an inherent value in nature; the debate hinges on how to prioritize limited conservation resources in the most cost-effective way.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Conservation biologists have started to collaborate with leading global economists to determine how to measure the wealth and services of nature and to make these values apparent in global market transactions.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] This system of accounting is called *natural capital* and would, for example, register the value of an ecosystem before it is cleared to make way for development.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] The WWF publishes its *Living Planet Report* and provides a global index of biodiversity by monitoring approximately 5,000 populations in 1,686 species of vertebrate (mammals, birds, fish, reptiles, and amphibians) and report on the trends in much the same way that the stock market is tracked.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] This method of measuring the global economic benefit of nature has been endorsed by the G8+5 leaders and the European Commission.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Nature sustains many ecosystem services that benefit humanity.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Many of the Earth's ecosystem services are public goods without a market and therefore no price or value.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] When the *stock market* registers a financial crisis, traders on Wall Street are not in the business of trading stocks for much of the planet's living natural capital stored in ecosystems.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] There is no natural stock market with investment portfolios into sea horses, amphibians, insects, and other creatures that provide a sustainable supply of ecosystem services that are valuable to society.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] The ecological footprint of society has exceeded the bio-regenerative capacity limits of the planet's ecosystems by about 30 percent, which is the same percentage of vertebrate populations that have registered decline from 1970 through 2005.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] There is a relationship, a correlation, between markets and natural capital, and social income inequity and biodiversity loss.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] This means that there are greater rates of biodiversity loss in places where the inequity of wealth is greatest, an example of this would be the Perdido Key beach mouse.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] This is an endangered species that its demis started because of continued development along beaches, these mice leave in sand dunes and play an important role within this ecosystem.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] These mice help the grass grow inside the sandunes, they eat this grass and then this leads to then spreading seeds throughout the beach creating more grass.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Sand dunes may not seem that important but they do act as a barrier for any sort of storm coming from the ocean such as hurricanes.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Although a direct market comparison of natural capital is likely insufficient in terms of human value, one measure of ecosystem services suggests the contribution amounts to trillions of dollars yearly.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] For example, one segment of North American forests has been assigned an annual value of 250 billion dollars; as another example, honey bee pollination is estimated to provide between 10 and 18 billion dollars of value yearly.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] The value of ecosystem services on one New Zealand island has been imputed to be as great as the GDP of that region.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] This planetary wealth is being lost at an incredible rate as the demands of human society is exceeding the bio-regenerative capacity of the Earth.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] While biodiversity and ecosystems are resilient, the danger of losing them is that humans cannot recreate many ecosystem functions through technological innovation.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Some species, called a *keystone species* form a central supporting hub unique to their ecosystem.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] The loss of such a species results in a collapse in ecosystem function, as well as the loss of coexisting species.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Keystone species are usually predators due to their ability to control the population of prey in their ecosystem.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] The importance of a keystone species was shown by the extinction of the Steller's sea cow (*Hydrodamalis gigas*) through its interaction with sea otters, sea urchins, and kelp.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Kelp beds grow and form nurseries in shallow waters to shelter creatures that support the food chain.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Sea urchins feed on kelp, while sea otters feed on sea urchins.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] With the rapid decline of sea otters due to overhunting, sea urchin populations grazed unrestricted on the kelp beds and the ecosystem collapsed.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Left unchecked, the urchins destroyed the shallow water kelp communities that supported the Steller's sea cow's diet and hastened their demise.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] The sea otter was thought to be a keystone species because the coexistence of many ecological associates in the kelp beds relied upon otters for their survival.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] However this was later questioned by Turvey and Risley, who showed that hunting alone would have driven the Steller's sea cow extinct.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] An *indicator species* has a narrow set of ecological requirements, therefore they become useful targets for observing the health of an ecosystem.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Some animals, such as amphibians with their semi-permeable skin and linkages to wetlands, have an acute sensitivity to environmental harm and thus may serve as a *miner's canary*.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Indicator species are monitored in an effort to capture environmental degradation through pollution or some other link to proximate human activities.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Government regulators, consultants, or NGOs regularly monitor indicator species, however, there are limitations coupled with many practical considerations that must be followed for the approach to be effective.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] It is generally recommended that multiple indicators (genes, populations, species, communities, and landscape) be monitored for effective conservation measurement that prevents harm to the complex, and often unpredictable, response from ecosystem dynamics (Noss, 1997).
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] An example of an *umbrella species* is the monarch butterfly, because of its lengthy migrations and aesthetic value.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] The monarch migrates across North America, covering multiple ecosystems and so requires a large area to exist.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Any protections afforded to the monarch butterfly will at the same time umbrella many other species and habitats.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] An umbrella species is often used as *flagship species*, which are species, such as the giant panda, the blue whale, the tiger, the mountain gorilla and the monarch butterfly, that capture the public's attention and attract support for conservation measures.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p01] Paradoxically, however, conservation bias towards flagship species sometimes threatens other species of chief concern.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] Conservation biologists study trends and process from the paleontological past to the ecological present as they gain an understanding of the context related to species extinction.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] It is generally accepted that there have been five major global mass extinctions that register in Earth's history.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] These include: the Ordovician (440 mya), Devonian (370 mya), Permian–Triassic (252 mya), Triassic–Jurassic (201 mya), and Cretaceous–Paleogene extinction event (66 mya) extinction spasms.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] The latest *Living Planet Report* by the World Wide Fund for Nature estimates that we have exceeded the bio-regenerative capacity of the planet, requiring 1.6 Earths to support the demands placed on our natural resources.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] Conservation biologists are dealing with and have published evidence from all corners of the planet indicating that humanity may be causing the sixth and fastest planetary extinction event.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] It has been suggested that an unprecedented number of species is becoming extinct in what is known as the Holocene extinction event.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] The global extinction rate may be approximately 1,000 times higher than the natural background extinction rate.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] It is estimated that two-thirds of all mammal genera and one-half of all mammal species weighing at least 44 kilograms (97 lb) have gone extinct in the last 50,000 years.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] The Global Amphibian Assessment reports that amphibians are declining on a global scale faster than any other vertebrate group, with over 32 percent of all surviving species being threatened with extinction.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] The surviving populations are in continual decline in 43 percent of those that are threatened.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] Since the mid-1980s the actual rates of extinction have exceeded 211 times rates measured from the fossil record.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] However, "The current amphibian extinction rate may range from 25,039 to 45,474 times the background extinction rate for amphibians." The global extinction trend occurs in every major vertebrate group that is being monitored.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] For example, 23 percent of all mammals and 12 percent of all birds are Red Listed by the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN), meaning they too are threatened with extinction.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] Even though extinction is natural, the decline in species is happening at such an incredible rate that evolution can simply not match, therefore, leading to the greatest continual mass extinction on Earth.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] Humans have dominated the planet and our high consumption of resources, along with the pollution generated is affecting the environments in which other species live.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] There are a wide variety of species that humans are working to protect such as the Hawaiian Crow and the Whooping Crane of Texas.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] People can also take action on preserving species by advocating and voting for global and national policies that improve climate, under the concepts of climate mitigation and climate restoration.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] The Earth's oceans demand particular attention as climate change continues to alter pH levels, making it uninhabitable for organisms with shells which dissolve as a result.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] Global assessments of coral reefs of the world continue to report drastic and rapid rates of decline.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] By 2000, 27 percent of the world's coral reef ecosystems had effectively collapsed.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] The largest period of decline occurred in a dramatic "bleaching" event in 1998, where approximately 16 percent of all the coral reefs in the world disappeared in less than a year.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] *Coral bleaching* is caused by a mixture of environmental stresses, including increases in ocean temperatures and acidity, causing both the release of symbiotic algae and death of corals.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] Decline and extinction risk in coral reef biodiversity has risen dramatically in the past ten years.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] The loss of coral reefs, which are predicted to go extinct in the next century, threatens the balance of global biodiversity, will have huge economic impacts, and endangers food security for hundreds of millions of people.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] Conservation biology plays an important role in international agreements covering the world's oceans and other issues pertaining to biodiversity.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] The oceans are threatened by acidification due to an increase in CO2 levels.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] This is a most serious threat to societies relying heavily upon oceanic natural resources.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] A concern is that the majority of all marine species will not be able to evolve or acclimate in response to the changes in the ocean chemistry.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] The prospects of averting mass extinction seems unlikely when "90% of all of the large (average approximately ≥50 kg), open ocean tuna, billfishes, and sharks in the ocean" are reportedly gone.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] Given the scientific review of current trends, the ocean is predicted to have few surviving multi-cellular organisms with only microbes left to dominate marine ecosystems.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] Serious concerns also being raised about taxonomic groups that do not receive the same degree of social attention or attract funds as the vertebrates.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] These include fungal (including lichen-forming species), invertebrate (particularly insect) and plant communities where the vast majority of biodiversity is represented.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] Conservation of fungi and conservation of insects, in particular, are both of pivotal importance for conservation biology.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] As mycorrhizal symbionts, and as decomposers and recyclers, fungi are essential for sustainability of forests.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] The value of insects in the biosphere is enormous because they outnumber all other living groups in measure of species richness.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] The greatest bulk of biomass on land is found in plants, which is sustained by insect relations.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] This great ecological value of insects is countered by a society that often reacts negatively toward these aesthetically 'unpleasant' creatures.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] One area of concern in the insect world that has caught the public eye is the mysterious case of missing honey bees (*Apis mellifera*).
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] Honey bees provide an indispensable ecological services through their acts of pollination supporting a huge variety of agriculture crops.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] The use of honey and wax have become vastly used throughout the world.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] The sudden disappearance of bees leaving empty hives or colony collapse disorder (CCD) is not uncommon.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] However, in 16-month period from 2006 through 2007, 29 percent of 577 beekeepers across the United States reported CCD losses in up to 76 percent of their colonies.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] This sudden demographic loss in bee numbers is placing a strain on the agricultural sector.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] The cause behind the massive declines is puzzling scientists.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] Pests, pesticides, and global warming are all being considered as possible causes.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] Another highlight that links conservation biology to insects, forests, and climate change is the mountain pine beetle (*Dendroctonus ponderosae*) epidemic of British Columbia, Canada, which has infested 470,000 km2 (180,000 sq mi) of forested land since 1999.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] An action plan has been prepared by the Government of British Columbia to address this problem.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] A large proportion of parasite species are threatened by extinction.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] A few of them are being eradicated as pests of humans or domestic animals; however, most of them are harmless.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] Parasites also make up a significant amount of global biodiversity, given that they make up a large proportion of all species on earth, making them of increasingly prevalent conservation interest.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] Threats include the decline or fragmentation of host populations, or the extinction of host species.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] Parasites are intricately woven into ecosystems and food webs, thereby occupying valuable roles in ecosystem structure and function.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] Today, many threats to biodiversity exist.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] An acronym that can be used to express the top threats of present-day H.I.P.P.O stands for Habitat Loss, Invasive Species, Pollution, Human Population, and Overharvesting.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] The primary threats to biodiversity are habitat destruction (such as deforestation, agricultural expansion, urban development), and overexploitation (such as wildlife trade).
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] Habitat fragmentation also poses challenges, because the global network of protected areas only covers 11.5 percent of the Earth's surface.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] A significant consequence of fragmentation and lack of linked protected areas is the reduction of animal migration on a global scale.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] Considering that billions of tonnes of biomass are responsible for nutrient cycling across the Earth, the reduction of migration is a serious matter for conservation biology.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] However, human activities need not necessarily cause irreparable harm to the biosphere.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] With conservation management and planning for biodiversity at all levels, from genes to ecosystems, there are examples where humans mutually coexist in a sustainable way with nature.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] Even with the current threats to biodiversity there are ways we can improve the current condition and start anew.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] Many of the threats to biodiversity, including disease and climate change, are reaching inside borders of protected areas, leaving them 'not-so protected' (e.g.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] Climate change, for example, is often cited as a serious threat in this regard, because there is a feedback loop between species extinction and the release of carbon dioxide into the atmosphere.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] Ecosystems store and cycle large amounts of carbon which regulates global conditions.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] In present day, there have been major climate shifts with temperature changes making survival of some species difficult.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] The effects of global warming add a catastrophic threat toward a mass extinction of global biological diversity.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] Numerous more species are predicted to face unprecedented levels of extinction risk due to population increase, climate change and economic development in the future.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] Conservationists have claimed that not all the species can be saved, and they have to decide which their efforts should be used to protect.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] This concept is known as the Conservation Triage.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] The extinction threat is estimated to range from 15 to 37 percent of all species by 2050, or 50 percent of all species over the next 50 years.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/conservation-biology-p02] The current extinction rate is 100–100,000 times more rapid today than the last several billion years.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] By far, the direct cause of most deforestation is agriculture.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] In 2025 nearly 90% of global deforestation was caused by agriculture, with cropland expansion and pasture creation the primary drivers, this is up from more than 80% in 2012.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Forests are being converted to plantations for coffee, palm oil, rubber and various other popular products.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Livestock grazing also drives deforestation.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Further drivers are the wood industry (logging), urbanization and mining.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] The effects of climate change are another cause via the increased risk of wildfires (see deforestation and climate change).
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Deforestation results in habitat destruction which in turn leads to biodiversity loss.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Deforestation also leads to extinction of animals and plants, changes to the local climate, and displacement of indigenous people who live in forests.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Deforested regions often also suffer from other environmental problems such as desertification and soil erosion.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Another problem is that deforestation reduces the uptake of carbon dioxide (carbon sequestration) from the atmosphere.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] This reduces the potential of forests to assist with climate change mitigation.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] The role of forests in capturing and storing carbon and mitigating climate change is also important for the agricultural sector.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] The reason for this linkage is that the effects of climate change on agriculture pose new risks to global food systems.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Since 1990, it is estimated that some 420 million hectares of forest have been lost through conversion to other land uses, although the rate of deforestation has decreased over the past three decades.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Between 2015 and 2020, the rate of deforestation was estimated at 10 million hectares per year, down from 16 million hectares per year in the 1990s.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] The area of primary forest worldwide has decreased by over 80 million hectares since 1990.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] More than 100 million hectares of forests are adversely affected by forest fires, pests, diseases, invasive species, drought and adverse weather events.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Deforestation is defined as the conversion of forest to other land uses (regardless of whether it is human-induced).
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] The world has a total forest area of 4.14 billion hectares (ha), which is 32% of the global land area and equivalent to 0.50 ha of forest per person.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] The tropical domain has the largest proportion of the world’s forests (45%), followed by the boreal, temperate and subtropical domains.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Of the regions, Europe has the largest forest area, accounting for 25% of the world’s total.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] South America has the highest proportion of forest, at 49% of the total land area.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] More than half (54%) of the world’s forests is in only five countries (in descending order by area).; Russia, Brazil, Canada, the United States of America and China.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] The rate of net forest loss decreased globally from 10.7 million ha per year between 1990–2000 to 3.68 million ha per year in 2000–2015 due mainly to large increases in forest area in Canada, China, the Russian Federation and the United States of America.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] The annual rate of net forest loss increased in the period 2015–2025, to 4.12 million ha, due to a reduction in the rate of forest gain (i.e. afforestation and natural forest expansion).
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] The FAO estimates that the global forest carbon stock has decreased 0.9%, and tree cover 4.2% between 1990 and 2020.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] As of 2019 there is still disagreement about whether the global forest is shrinking or not: "While above-ground biomass carbon stocks are estimated to be declining in the tropics, they are increasing globally due to increasing stocks in temperate and boreal forest.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Deforestation in many countries—both naturally occurring and human-induced—is an ongoing issue.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Between 2000 and 2012, 2.3 million square kilometres (890,000 square miles) of forests around the world were cut down.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Deforestation and forest degradation continue to take place at alarming rates, which contributes significantly to the ongoing loss of biodiversity.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Forest area increased in Asia between 1990 and 2025, albeit at a lower rate in the most recent decade.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Forest area also increased over the 35-year period in Europe and to a lesser extent in North and Central America.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Forest area has declined substantially in Africa and South America since 1990, although the rate of loss slowed in both regions in the decade to 2025.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] An estimated 489 million ha of forest has been lost worldwide through deforestation since 1990, but the rate of loss has slowed.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] The deforestation rate was estimated at 10.9 million ha per year in 2015–2025, down from 13.6 million ha per year in 2000–2015 and 17.6 million ha per year in 1990–2000.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] The rate of forest expansion slowed from 9.88 million ha per year in 2000–2015 to 6.78 million ha per year in the decade to 2025.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Deforestation is more extreme in tropical and subtropical forests in emerging economies.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] More than half of all plant and land animal species in the world live in tropical forests.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] As a result of deforestation, only 6.2 million square kilometres (2.4 million square miles) remain of the original 16 million square kilometres (6 million square miles) of tropical rainforest that formerly covered the Earth.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] More than 3.6 million hectares of virgin tropical forest was lost in 2018.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] The global annual net loss of trees is estimated to be approximately 10 billion.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] According to the Global Forest Resources Assessment 2020 the global average annual deforested land in the 2015–2020 demi-decade was 10 million hectares and the average annual forest area net loss in the 2000–2010 decade was 4.7 million hectares.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] The world has lost 178 million ha of forest since 1990, which is an area about the size of Libya.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] An analysis of global deforestation patterns in 2021 showed that patterns of trade, production, and consumption drive deforestation rates in complex ways.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] While the location of deforestation can be mapped, it does not always match where the commodity is consumed.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] For example, consumption patterns in G7 countries are estimated to cause an average loss of 3.9 trees per person per year.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] In other words, deforestation can be directly related to imports—for example, coffee.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] In 2023, the Global Forest Watch reported a 9% decline in tropical primary forest loss compared to the previous year, with significant regional reductions in Brazil and Colombia overshadowed by increases elsewhere, leading to a 3.2% rise in global deforestation.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Massive wildfires in Canada, exacerbated by climate change, contributed to a 24% increase in global tree cover loss, highlighting the ongoing threats to forests essential for carbon storage and biodiversity.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Despite some progress, the overall trends in forest destruction and climate impacts remain off track.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] The period since 1950 has brought "the most rapid transformation of the human relationship with the natural world in the history of humankind".
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Through 2018, humans have reduced forest area by ~30% and grasslands/shrubs by ~68%, to make way for livestock grazing and crops for humans.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Global deforestation sharply accelerated around 1852.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] As of 1947, the planet had 15 to 16 million km2 (5.8 to 6.2 million mi2) of mature tropical forests, but by 2015, it was estimated that about half of these had been destroyed.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Total land coverage by tropical rainforests decreased from 14% to 6%.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Much of this loss happened between 1960 and 1990, when 20% of all tropical rainforests were destroyed.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] At this rate, extinction of such forests is projected to occur by the mid-21st century.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] In the early 2000s, some scientists predicted that unless significant measures (such as seeking out and protecting old growth forests that have not been disturbed) are taken on a worldwide basis, by 2030 there will only be 10% remaining, with another 10% in a degraded condition.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] 80% will have been lost, and with them hundreds of thousands of irreplaceable species.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Estimates vary widely as to the extent of deforestation in the tropics.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] In 2019, the world lost nearly 12 million hectares of tree cover.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Nearly a third of that loss, 3.8 million hectares, occurred within humid tropical primary forests, areas of mature rainforest that are especially important for biodiversity and carbon storage.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] This is equivalent to losing an area of primary forest the size of a football pitch every six seconds.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] The rate of global tree cover loss has approximately doubled since 2001, to an annual loss approaching an area the size of Italy.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] forest in the tropics has varied from year to year, but remains consistently higher than preceding decades.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] A 2002 analysis of satellite imagery suggested that the rate of deforestation in the humid tropics (approximately 5.8 million hectares per year) was roughly 23% lower than the most commonly quoted rates.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] A 2005 report by the United Nations Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) estimated that although the Earth's total forest area continued to decrease at about 13 million hectares per year, the global rate of deforestation had been slowing.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] On the other hand, a 2005 analysis of satellite images reveals that deforestation of the Amazon rainforest is twice as fast as scientists previously estimated.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] From 2010 to 2015, worldwide forest area decreased by 3.3 million ha per year, according to FAO.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] During this five-year period, the biggest forest area loss occurred in the tropics, particularly in South America and Africa.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Per capita forest area decline was also greatest in the tropics and subtropics but is occurring in every climatic domain (except in the temperate) as populations increase.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] An estimated 420 million ha of forest has been lost worldwide through deforestation since 1990, but the rate of forest loss has declined substantially.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] In the most recent five-year period (2015–2020), the annual rate of deforestation was estimated at 10 million ha, down from 12 million ha in 2010–2015.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] forest loss greatly exceeds that of other countries.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Overall, 20% of the Amazon rainforest has been "transformed" (deforested) and another 6% has been "highly degraded", causing Amazon Watch to warn that the Amazonia is in the midst of a tipping point crisis.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Africa had the largest annual rate of net forest loss in 2010–2020, at 3.9 million ha, followed by South America, at 2.6 million ha.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] The rate of net forest loss has increased in Africa in each of the three decades since 1990.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] It has declined substantially in South America, however, to about half the rate in 2010–2020 compared with 2000–2010.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Asia had the highest net gain of forest area in 2010–2020, followed by Oceania and Europe.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Nevertheless, both Europe and Asia recorded substantially lower rates of net gain in 2010–2020 than in 2000–2010.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Oceania experienced net losses of forest area in the decades 1990–2000 and 2000–2010.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Some claim that rainforests are being destroyed at an ever-quickening pace.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] The London-based Rainforest Foundation notes that "the UN figure is based on a definition of forest as being an area with as little as 10% actual tree cover, which would therefore include areas that are actually savanna-like ecosystems and badly damaged forests".
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Other critics of the FAO data point out that they do not distinguish between forest types, and that they are based largely on reporting from forestry departments of individual countries, which do not take into account unofficial activities like illegal logging.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Despite these uncertainties, there is agreement that destruction of rainforests remains a significant environmental problem.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] The rate of net forest loss declined from 7.8 million ha per year in the decade 1990–2000 to 5.2 million ha per year in 2000–2010 and 4.7 million ha per year in 2010–2020.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] The rate of decline of net forest loss slowed in the most recent decade due to a reduction in the rate of forest expansion.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] In many parts of the world, especially in East Asian countries, reforestation and afforestation are increasing the area of forested lands.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] The amount of forest has increased in 22 of the world's 50 most forested nations.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Asia as a whole gained 1 million hectares of forest between 2000 and 2005.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Tropical forest in El Salvador expanded more than 20% between 1992 and 2001.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Based on these trends, one study projects that global forestation will increase by 10%—an area the size of India—by 2050.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] 36% of globally planted forest area is in East Asia – around 950,000 square kilometers.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Rates of deforestation vary around the world.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Up to 90% of West Africa's coastal rainforests have disappeared since 1900.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Madagascar has lost 90% of its eastern rainforests.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] In South Asia, about 88% of the rainforests have been lost.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Mexico, India, the Philippines, Indonesia, Thailand, Burma, Malaysia, Bangladesh, China, Sri Lanka, Laos, Nigeria, the Democratic Republic of the Congo, Liberia, Guinea, Ghana and the Ivory Coast, have lost large areas of their rainforest.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Much of what remains of the world's rainforests is in the Amazon basin, where the Amazon rainforest covers approximately 4 million square kilometres.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Some 80% of the deforestation of the Amazon can be attributed to cattle ranching, as Brazil is the largest exporter of beef in the world.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] The Amazon region has become one of the largest cattle ranching territories in the world.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] The regions with the highest tropical deforestation rate between 2000 and 2005 were Central America—which lost 1.3% of its forests each year—and tropical Asia.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] In Central America, two-thirds of lowland tropical forests have been turned into pasture since 1950 and 40% of all the rainforests have been lost in the last 40 years.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Brazil has lost 90–95% of its Mata Atlântica forest.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Deforestation in Brazil increased by 88% for the month of June 2019, as compared with the previous year.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] However, Brazil still destroyed 1.3 million hectares in 2019.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Brazil is one of several countries that have declared their deforestation a national emergency.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] Paraguay was losing its natural semi-humid forests in the country's western regions at a rate of 15,000 hectares at a randomly studied 2-month period in 2010.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] In 2009, Paraguay's parliament refused to pass a law that would have stopped cutting of natural forests altogether.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] As of 2007, less than 50% of Haiti's forests remained.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] From 2015 to 2019, the rate of deforestation in the Democratic Republic of the Congo doubled.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] In 2021, deforestation of the Congolese rainforest increased by 5%.
[src:botanic-gardens-conservation-international/deforestation-p01] In 2011, Conservation International listed the top 10 most endangered forests, characterized by having all lost 90% or more of their original habitat, and each harboring at least 1500 endemic plant species (species found nowhere else in the world).
